<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Aug. 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Verizon, Unions Make 'Tentative' Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Verizon Communications and unions representing 50,000
workers reached a tentative agreement Sunday on a new three-year-contract as a
two-week strike affecting 25 million phone users in the East neared an end. The
agreement was struck with the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers
and one of two bargaining units for the Communications Workers of America
covering employees in New York and New England. Negotiations with another
bargaining unit for the CWA -- covering more than 35,000 workers in the Middle
Atlantic states -- continued.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Moroccan King Announces Oil Find
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- King Mohammed VI said Sunday that a large field of oil
and gas had been discovered near Morocco's eastern border. The king said the
find ''was good-quality and abundant,'' but he did not specify the amount
discovered near Talsint, about 60 miles from the border with gas-rich Algeria,
the official MAP news agency reported. Morocco has had no important oil or
natural gas reserves, importing virtually all its fuel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Polls: Salazar Leads in Chiapas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- Supporters of a candidate allied to Mexico's
president-elect celebrated in the streets after early results showed their
favorite ahead in Sunday's gubernatorial election. Pablo Salazar is seeking to
end the long domination of Mexico's impoverished Chiapas state by the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, pledging to step up efforts to end
the six-year-old Zapatista rebellion there. The election is seen as a major test
of the PRI's ability to rebound after Vicente Fox won Mexico's presidency on
July 2 and ended the PRI's 71-year reign in Mexico. By 10:30 p.m., Salazar, head
of an eight-party coalition including Fox's party, had a lead of 56 percent to
43 percent over the PRI's Sami David, with 48 percent of the vote counted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rescuers Cannot Get In Russian Sub
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Norwegian divers found no sign of life Sunday, after
struggling unsuccessfully to open the escape hatch on a nuclear submarine that
sank with 118 men aboard, . Russian officials said most of the vessel was
flooded in minutes when it went down and the country's navy has all but ruled
out hope that any of the crew remains alive nine days after the Kursk sank,
crippled by a massive explosion. The divers, working 350 feet below the surface
of the Barents Sea, found signs that some of the 118 crewmen may have tried to
get out but were unable to open the escape hatch.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.M. Pipeline Explosion Kills 10
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) -- An explosion of a natural gas pipeline just before
dawn Sunday swept flames down the river's banks and through the tents where two
families had been camping, killing 10 people, five of them children. The only
survivors, a man and his daughter-in-law, were in critical condition Sunday at a
Lubbock, Texas, hospital. Officials described the ruptured pipeline as a massive
flame-thrower that showered burning fuel on the victims. The explosion generated
heat so intense that sand melted into glass and concrete turned to powder, a
federal investigator said Sunday. Investigators say it likely will take several
months to determine what caused the rupture in the 30-inch-diameter pipe.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
2 Burkina Faso Bodyguards Sentenced
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) -- Two bodyguards of Burkina Faso's president
have been sentenced to 20 years in prison for torturing to death the driver of
the president's brother. A third bodyguard was sentenced to 10 years without
parole, and two more were acquitted. A military tribunal handed down the
verdicts Saturday night in this semi-desert West African nation. The men were
tried in the death of David Ouedraogo, the chauffeur for President Blaise
Compaore's younger brother, Francois.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices fell in early trading Monday following a
slip on Wall Street Friday. The Nikkei fell 64.77 points, or 0.39 percent, in
the first 30 minutes of morning trading. The index had gained 119.46 points, or
0.74 percent, Friday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Woods Wins PGA Title in Playoff
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Tiger Woods Sunday birdied the last two holes in
regulation and won the PGA Championship in a playoff over Bob May, becoming the
first player since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three majors in one year. Both made
five birdies, two sensational par saves and had a 31 on the back nine. Woods
outlasted May by taking only three putts in the three-hole playoff, the last one
a 2-foot par putt for his third consecutive major.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rangers Beat Red Sox 6-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Doug Davis pitched a nine-hitter and Frank Catalanotto drove
in three runs as the Texas Rangers beat the Boston Red Sox 6-2 Sunday night.
Catalanotto, who was 0-for-9 in the first three games of the series, gave the
Rangers a 2-1 lead with a double in the fifth inning, and helped Texas avoid a
sweep.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
