<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's President Faces Congress  </HEADLINE>
By LISA J. ADAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Vicente Fox achieved what some considered the
impossible by knocking the long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes another daunting battle: dealing with the most
independent Congress in Mexico's history. For the first time, no
party will have a majority in either house of Congress, meaning the
incoming president will have to wheel and deal like no other.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, presidents from the Institutional Revolutionary
Party -- known by its Spanish initials as the PRI -- simply passed
down legislative initiatives to be rubber stamped by the
party-dominated Congress.
</P>
<P>
   That had already begun to change some.
</P>
<P>
   Under President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, elected in 1988, a
reform was enacted prohibiting any party from having a two-thirds
majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1997 elections, the PRI lost its majority in the Chamber
of Deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, outgoing President Ernesto Zedillo has had to
tussle with Congress on issues ranging from bank bailouts to
budgets -- and was probably the first president to be defeated on a
major piece of legislation, failing in his effort to reform the
electricity industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Zedillo has held a trump card that Fox won't
possess when he takes office Dec. 1: a majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   With no such advantage, Fox will be forced to use his veto power
on some legislative issues, while facing potential battles on
matters requiring Senate approval, such as the appointment of
Supreme Court justices, ambassadors and attorney general, said
Benito Nacif, an analyst at the Center of Economic Investigation
and Instruction in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ''This president will be subjected to the most checks and
balances in Mexico's history,'' Nacif said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox won't even have the unquestioned support of his center-right
National Action Party. Contrary to a Mexican tradition in which the
ruling PRI has been synonymous with the government, Fox is
insisting that National Action operate separately, and as a check
on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''The PAN is a different animal,'' Nacif said. ''There will have
to be more negotiations with the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rodolfo Elizondo, a political affairs coordinator on Fox's
transition team, notes the president-elect already is opening the
way for negotiations with his messages of plurality, the naming of
a multiparty transition team and the inclusion of opposition party
leaders on a recent trip to South America.
</P>
<P>
   He says Fox's government will have something else going for it:
the popular clamor for change that swept the blunt-talking
candidate into office. If the PRI and the leftist Democratic
Revolution Party, which will be the two main opposition parties,
oppose reforms, ''they are going to have to pay a price for that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI may be inclined to cooperation rather than confrontation
in ''fear of being perceived as an obstacle to progress,'' said
analyst Delal Baer at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   That's the face the PRI is showing now. ''The attitude of the
PRI faction will be one of openness and disposition to dialogue,''
said Beatriz Paredes, who will lead the PRI bloc in the new House.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its defeat in the presidential race, the PRI remains a
force. It will have the largest number of lawmakers in both houses
of Congress and still controls numerous state and city governments,
so there isn't likely to be any large-scale defection of PRI
legislators to National Action or other parties, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Revolution, which finished third in the presidential
election and lost 74 of the 126 congressional seats it had won in
1997, also has promised to establish a relationship with Fox's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Like Zedillo, however, Fox is unlikely to form any permanent
congressional alliances, and will instead seek out new allies issue
by issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will see a test of his negotiating skills, his ability to
build consensus and bridges,'' Baer said. ''It's no accident that
every day the word consensus seems to slip out of his mouth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
