<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Lauds Eisenhower Building  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- From the North Lawn of the White House the
building bulks like a giant aircraft carrier, a prodigious,
gray-granite ship of state burdened with pillars, ornament and
history.
</P>
<P>
   Once denounced as an unfit architectural companion to the
chastely simple White House just across the way, the newly renamed
Eisenhower Executive Office Building has survived the whims of
architectural fashion and, ironically, even an Eisenhower-era
recommendation that it be demolished.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want it torn down; I think it's the greatest
monstrosity in America,'' former President Truman proclaimed in
1958.
</P>
<P>
   When the building was approved in 1869 as a new home for the
State, War and Navy departments, its design was seen as
state-of-the-art architecture, not a monstrosity. Architect Alfred
Mullet designed it in the florid, mansarded-roof, chimney-potted
style of the French Second Empire, including some 900 exterior
columns.
</P>
<P>
   Construction took 17 years, beginning in 1871 when U.S. Grant
was president, and it was quickly put to work.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four secretaries of state practiced diplomacy there, from
Hamilton Fish in the days of gaslight to George C. Marshall at the
opening of the nuclear age.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven future presidents walked the marble-tiled
corridors. One, William Howard Taft, was among the 21 secretaries
of war to use the building. Both Theodore and Franklin Roosevelt
served there as assistant secretaries of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight D. Eisenhower knew the building well during his long
service as a military aide in the War Department in the 1930s, long
before he rose to five-star general and became the 34th president.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, workmen erected bronze plaques bearing his name,
carrying out a congressional directive to change its identity as
the Old Executive Office Building, or EOB.
</P>
<P>
   The EOB shorthand stuck even after a new executive office
building was built nearby several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Every vice president since Lyndon Johnson has had his principal
office in the EOB; three of them -- Johnson, Gerald Ford and George
Bush -- have become president.
</P>
<P>
   The building has provided office space for presidential staffs
since the State, War and Navy departments moved elsewhere, leaving
a legacy of a thousand treaty signings and recollections of the
Spanish-American War and World War I.
</P>
<P>
   In Room 208, on Dec. 7, 1941, Secretary of State Cordell Hull
applied muleskinner profanity as he received ambassadors from Japan
just hours after Japanese forces had attacked Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   In Room 474, on Jan. 19, 1955, Eisenhower conducted the first
televised presidential news conference and set a precedent for a
new age of White House communications.
</P>
<P>
   President Nixon spent much time isolated in his EOB hideaway as
the Watergate scandal erupted. It was there, he said in his
memoirs, that he decided to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Lt. Col. Oliver North spent a late night shredding papers
in the building as the Iran-Contra scandal threatened to engulf the
Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   A grinning President Clinton rode a bicycle down some of the
nearly two miles of corridors in a humorous video shown earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents no longer see the Old EOB as a candidate for the
wrecking ball, but in the post-World War II years the opulent old
pile seemed like an embarrassing monument to wretched
overindulgence.
</P>
<P>
   ''People with the gift of taste were ashamed of it,'' E.J.
Applewhite wrote in ''Washington Itself,'' an informal guide to the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   What appeared to be a death sentence came in 1957 when an
Eisenhower administration commission recommended the building be
demolished ''in view of its recognized faults and deficiencies of
design.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower said that while he'd leave the decision to the
experts, he did have a personal opinion. ''I worked nine years in
this building, and so from sentiment's sake, I would probably say I
wouldn't want to see it torn down,'' he said at 1957 news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The first signs of the historic preservation movement were
beginning to stir. In the Kennedy administration, a new Commission
of Fine Arts recommended the building be spared and restored.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration began in the 1980s, removing World War II
blackout paint from stained-glass domes, replacing thousands of
windows, fixing the slate-tiled roof and preserving the 4,000 brass
staircase balusters.
</P>
<P>
   Also preserved were the 26 outdoor flowerpot urns installed in
1913 during the six-month reign of Capt. Douglas MacArthur, another
future five-star general, as building superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Public tours, by reservation only, showcase the refurbished
Indian Treaty Room, two jewel-case libraries with cast-iron
balconies and the vice president's ceremonial office, restored to
its appearance in 1900 when it was the office of the secretary of
the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower Executive Office Building site:
http://www.whitehouse.gov/WH/Tours/OEOB/html/welcome--f.html
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lawrence L. Knutson has covered the White House,
Congress and Washington's history for more than 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 0120 </TRAILER>
