<DOCNO> APW20000821.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Search For Tax Violations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China will audit all government and Communist
Party officials when they leave office, intensifying efforts to
combat corruption that is eroding public support for communist
rule, state media said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The government's National Audit Office will extend the reach of
current investigations by bringing ministry-level officials under
scrutiny -- a ''new iron fist'' in the fight against graft, the
official newspaper China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
   It quoted Li Jinhua, the office's auditor-general, as saying the
aim was to make routine a system in which every official is checked
upon leaving or retiring from their post.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest step in China's campaign to stop corruption. The
highest-level politician caught so far was Cheng Kejie, 66, a
former deputy chairman of the legislature who was sentenced to
death July 31 for amassing $4.9 million in bribes.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials approaching retirement are thought to be
especially vulnerable to corruption, with some amassing funds to
support themselves after they leave office.
</P>
<P>
   The China Daily said the new auditing system has already been
applied to officials at the county-level and below, the heads of
state-run firms and provincial government bureau chiefs in eastern
Zhejiang province.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the Communist Party on Sunday
announced a 10-year plan to reform the civil service. Among the
changes will be new regulations to curb corruption in promotions of
government and party officials, the state-run Xinhua News Agency
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
