<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 29; Nasdaq Up 21  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were higher Monday morning as many
technology shares extended gains that began during a rally last
week.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half-hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 29.03 points at 11,075.51.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.34 points at 1,496.06
and the Nasdaq composite index was up 21.42 at 3,951.76.
</P>
<P>
   Trading has been light in recent days as traders look ahead to
Tuesday's Federal Reserve meeting. Investors are hoping that the
Fed has finished with its credit-tightening campaign and will leave
interest rates alone for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates six times in the past 14
months in an effort to slow the economy and stave off inflation.
The strategy appears to be working, as a number of economic
indicators released in recent weeks have indicated that the economy
is still growing but inflation hasn't reached dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.40 points at 516.91.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.5 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.4 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.1 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
