<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 44; Nasdaq Adds 52  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock moved higher Monday on optimism that the
Federal Reserve Board will leave interest rates alone Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In midmorning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 43.96 at 11,090.44.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also were higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 9.64 at 1,501.36, and the
Nasdaq composite index was up 51.75 at 3,982.09.
</P>
<P>
   Trading has been light during recent sessions as traders look
ahead to Tuesday's Federal Reserve meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say most investors believe the Fed is finished with its
credit-tightening campaign and will leave interest rates alone for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what's been driving the markets for the past three
weeks,'' said Jack Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at
Advest Inc. ''The market is pretty much convinced that the Fed will
do nothing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates six times in the past 14
months in an effort to slow the economy and stave off inflation.
The strategy appears to be working, as a number of economic
indicators released in recent weeks have indicated that the economy
is still growing but inflation hasn't reached dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
   Technology issues fueled Monday's gains, extending a rally that
began last week. Widely-held benchmark stocks led the way,
including Intel, up $3.203 to $73.766, and Cisco Systems, up $1.563
at $65.063.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues slightly outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 223.26 million shares, well
below Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 2.70 at 518.21.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
