<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 34; Nasdaq Adds 48  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher Monday on optimism that the
Federal Reserve Board will leave interest rates alone Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In midmorning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 33.70 at 11,080.18.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also were higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 9.30 at 1,501.02, and the
Nasdaq composite index was up 47.61 at 3,977.95.
</P>
<P>
   Trading has been light during recent sessions as traders look
ahead to Tuesday's Federal Reserve meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say most investors believe the Fed is finished with its
credit-tightening campaign and will leave interest rates alone for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what's been driving the markets for the past three
weeks,'' said Jack Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at
Advest Inc. ''The market is pretty much convinced that the Fed will
do nothing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates six times in the past 14
months in an effort to slow the economy and stave off inflation.
The strategy appears to be working, as a number of economic
indicators released in recent weeks have indicated that the economy
is still growing but inflation hasn't reached dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
   Technology issues, led by chip maker Intel, fueled Monday's
gains, extending a rally in the tech sector that began last week.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's shares rose $2.812 to $73.375 after an analyst raised
his future earnings forecasts for the number one maker of computer
chips. The analyst said Intel's third quarter inventory is already
sold out, news that bodes well for the entire computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications parts makers also remained strong, following
up on last week's gains. Ciena Corp. rose $3.562 to $180.25, and
Copper Mountain was up $4.563 to $68.563.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues slightly outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 330.53 million shares, well
below Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 2.37 at 517.88.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
