<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak's Chief of Staff Resigns  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Angry door-slamming in the prime minister's
office and Monday's sudden resignation of a top aide, the second
within a week, are highlighting Ehud Barak's growing political
woes.
</P>
<P>
   With his coalition in a shambles and early elections apparently
inevitable, Barak is now being taken to task for his high-handed
leadership style, with former allies complaining that he often
ignores advice and fails to delegate responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli leader's counteroffensive -- an announcement that he
is launching a major secular rights crusade for a constitution and
civil marriage laws -- was dismissed as a clumsy attempt to win back
disappointed voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is desperate,'' political commentator Hanan Crystal said of
the ex-army chief once widely admired for his cool under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's political survival depends largely on whether he will be
able to conclude a peace agreement with the Palestinians before the
Knesset, or legislature, reconvenes in late October.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Barak wraps up a deal, which at this stage remains
doubtful because talks are deadlocked over control of Jerusalem, he
would not be able to ratify it. The prime minister lost his
parliamentary majority before leaving for last month's Mideast
summit at Camp David, with three of six parties quitting his
coalition. His efforts to lure the ultra-Orthodox Shas party back
into his government failed for good over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a treaty, Barak is expected to call early
elections that would serve as a referendum on the terms of
Palestinian statehood. If peace talks collapse, Barak may not be
able to cling to power: Former allies, including Shas and Israel
B'Aliya, a faction representing Russian immigrants, are now siding
with Likud, the hawkish leading opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's announcement over the weekend that he plans to launch
nothing short of a ''secular revolution'' -- an open challenge to
the powerful religious parties -- was widely seen as an attempt to
boost his re-election agenda in case he has to face voters without
a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister apparently hopes to win back the support of
immigrants from the former Soviet Union. They have deserted him in
droves, both because he reneged on promises to stand up to the
religious parties and because they oppose land concessions to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal said the gamble could pay off. However, the prime
minister's plan was largely met by scorn and skepticism Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''A situation in which a prime minister with 42 (of 120) votes
in the Knesset announces his intention to pass a constitution is
similar to Albania declaring war on the United States,''
commentator Shahar Ilan wrote in the Haaretz daily.
</P>
<P>
   Others criticized him for not consulting with his advisers
before launching an undertaking of such magnitude. Barak is now on
the record as the first prime minister who wants to try to turn
Israel into a secular state, but he never consulted leading members
of his Labor Party or senior aides before going public with the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   His go-it-alone style has angered his closest advisers,
including Haim Mendel-Shaked, who resigned Monday as the chief of
staff in the prime minister's office. Only a week ago,
Mendel-Shaked's deputy quit in anger. Both men served under Barak
when he commanded the army's elite commando unit, Sayeret Matkal.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper reports said the rivalries in Barak's office were so
intense that Israel's security was at risk. The Yediot Ahronot
daily said Barak's senior security adviser, Danny Yatom, was barely
on speaking terms with the heads of the two major security
services, the Mossad and the Shin Bet.
</P>
<P>
   ''With his (Barak's) chaotic style ... this explosion was just a
matter of time,'' political commentator Emanuel Rosen said of the
name-calling in Barak's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 1340 </TRAILER>
