<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suharto Trial Start Seen Next Week  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesian ex-President Suharto's
trial on corruption charges is expected to start next week, with
the exact date and venue to be announced on Wednesday, court
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta Judge Lalu Mariyun, who will oversee the trial as part
of a five-judge panel, met police and officials from the Attorney
General's Office on Monday to discuss logistics, officials at the
South Jakarta Court said. Mariyun would hold a news conference on
Wednesday, they said.
</P>
<P>
   One court official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Aug. 31 had been penciled in as the starting date.
</P>
<P>
   He said a building belonging to Ministry of Agriculture in the
south of the capital had been chosen as the venue. Hearing rooms at
the South Jakarta Court are too small to accommodate the trial,
which is expected to attract hundreds of journalists and
spectators, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Student protesters, who have repeatedly gone into the streets
demanding Suharto's prosecution, are also expected to stage
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, 79, ruled Indonesia for three decades, but was forced
from power two years ago by pro-democracy protests. His prosecution
is regarded as a crucial test of the 10-month-old government of
President Abdurrahman Wahid, who has vowed to clean up the endemic
corruption that riddles the world's fourth most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors have charged Suharto with siphoning off at
least $570 million in state funds through a complex network of
charities under his control. The former dictator, who like many
Indonesians uses one name, has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   If he is convicted, he could spend the rest of his life behind
bars, although Wahid has offered a pardon in exchange for the
return of any ill-gotten gains.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's attorneys have said he should not be forced into a
courtroom because a series of recent strokes damaged his brain.
They claim his memory and ability to answer questions have been
badly affected.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians have examined Suharto on several occasions recently,
and he has undergone a number of brain scans. Attorney General
Marzuki Darusman says medical tests show that Suharto is fit to
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto had been under house arrest since May. His detention
status was changed recently to allow him to travel around, but not
outside of, Jakarta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 1403 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
