<HEADLINE> US: Retaliation for Congo Expulsions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- The United States is considering ''an
appropriate and commensurate response'' to the Congolese
government's expulsion of two U.S. diplomats, the State Department
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Congo ordered press officer Denise Burgess and
political counselor Roger James Moran to leave for making
statements it contended were inconsistent with their diplomatic
role.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Monday the two
have since returned to Washington. U.S. Ambassador William Swing
called Congolese President Laurent Kabila on Saturday to protest
the expulsions.
</P>
<P>
   Congolese officials said the two were ordered home for
objectionable statements made to civil society leaders at a
diplomatic function.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher had no comment on the precise nature of the statements
except that some allegations by Congolese officials were
''outrageous and false.''
</P>
</TEXT>
