<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea Ex-Spy Seeks Repatriation  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A convicted North Korean spy claimed
Monday that the South Korean government is using an oath he signed
under pressure to deny him the right to return home when other
spies are repatriated next month.
</P>
<P>
   Chung Sun Taek, 79, signed an oath disavowing communism in 1989
so he could be released from prison after more than three decades.
He declared the oath invalid Monday and accused the Seoul
government of using it as a pretext not to send him back.
</P>
<P>
   At a historic summit of the two Koreas, the Seoul government
promised to repatriate all convicted Northern spies who want to
return. Last week, South Korea notified the North of the names of
62 ex-spies, who served 18 to 45 years in prison, it plans to
repatriate on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul says signing an oath is a legal matter that binds
signatories to honor South Korea's political and social systems, so
keeping them in the South does not violate the summit agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Chung and a female North Korean guerrilla, who signed an oath in
1985 under similar conditions and now wants to go home, are not on
the list. Seoul officials said the two are among about two dozen
ex-spies who were released in return for the oath.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I can't go home because of the oath, which I had to sign
under unbearable conditions, what is the purpose of seeking
reconciliation between the North and South?'' Chung asked in an
appeal to President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
   Chung read the appeal at a news conference arranged by
supporters. On hand were 30 ex-spies who will be repatriated. The
67-year-old female guerrilla, Chung Sun Duk, who was hospitalized
because of a serious illness, was not present.
</P>
<P>
   Chung Sun Taek, who spent 31 years and five months in a
12-square-foot prison cell, was arrested the day after he arrived
in Seoul in 1958 on a mission to win over a college friend who
worked as a television drama writer. He said he signed the oath on
the recommendation of doctors who said his health would improve if
he left the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Chung said he confirmed through a friend in Germany in 1998 that
his four children, ranging in age from 43 to 52, were alive in the
North. He said his wife had died several years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After taking office in 1998, the Kim Dae-jung government
unconditionally released all communist spies from prison but barred
them from leaving the country without government approval.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Unification Minister Park Jae-kyu said that the
repatriation of South Korean prisoners of war living in North Korea
might be discussed at a high-level inter-Korean meeting in
Pyongyang Aug. 29-31.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should return North Korean spies and have the POWs sent
back home,'' a ministry spokesman, Chung Kang-kyu, quoted the
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul officials say some 40,000 South Korean prisoners of war
never returned home after the 1950-1953 Korean War and that,
allowing for defections, 300 POWs are believed to be living in the
North today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 1521 </TRAILER>
