<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 6; Nasdaq Down 7  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks prices retreated Monday, erasing earlier
gains as most investors stayed out of the game one day ahead of the
Federal Reserve Board's decision on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In midafternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 5.86 at 11,040.62.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 0.45 at 1,495.92, and the
Nasdaq composite index was down 7.40 at 3,922.94.
</P>
<P>
   Trading has been light during recent sessions as traders look
ahead to Tuesday's Federal Reserve meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said most investors stayed on the sidelines Monday, not
willing to gamble one way or the other on whether the Fed will
increase rates or leave them stable.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, conventional wisdom holds that the Fed is finished
with its credit-tightening campaign and will leave interest rates
alone for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what's been driving the markets for the past three
weeks,'' said Jack Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at
Advest Inc. ''The market is pretty much convinced that the Fed will
do nothing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates six times in the past 14
months in an effort to slow the economy and stave off inflation.
The strategy appears to be working, as a number of economic
indicators released in recent weeks have signaled that the economy
is still growing but inflation hasn't reached dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sector continued to show weakness on fears that
second-half profits may be hurt by the cooling economy. Dow
component Wal-mart Stores was down $1.75, or 3 percent, at $48.75.
</P>
<P>
   Technology issues, led by chip maker Intel, extended a rally
that began last week.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's shares retreated from gains of more than a dollar, but
were still up 31.20 cents after an analyst raised his future
earnings forecasts for the number one maker of computer chips. The
analyst said Intel's third quarter inventory is already sold out,
news that bodes well for the entire computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications parts makers also remained strong, following
up on last week's gains. Ciena Corp. rose $4.125 to $180.813, and
Copper Mountain was up $4.625 to $68.625.
</P>
<P>
   And Clearnet Communications, which operates a digital telecom
network, rose $12.938 to $43.938 after Canadian phone company Telus
Corp. agreed to buy the wireless service provider for $4.48 billion
in cash, stock and assumed debt. The announcement boosted wireless
stocks across the board.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues slightly outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 581.33 million shares, well
below Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.19 at 515.32.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
