<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State cemeteries agency urges fight against West Nile mosquitoes  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The Pataki administration is seeking to
choke off possible breeding grounds for mosquitoes which carry the
West Nile virus at cemeteries around the state.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Division of Cemeteries said it wants the 2,000
cemeteries it regulates across the state to make sure that
fountains, reflecting pools and flower vases filled with water are
not allowed to become the stagnant breeding habitats for
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the division, Richard Fishman, said cemetery
operators have been ''very receptive'' so far to his agency's
efforts to reduce the risk of disease-bearing mosquitoes breeding
at cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   The division said it started working with officials in New York
City in April when the West Nile virus re-emerged this year in the
five boroughs. Cemeteries have been one of the focuses of spraying
to kill mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   With state Health Commissioner Dr. Antonia Novello acknowledging
that it is probable the West Nile virus has spread throughout the
state - as reflected by dead birds with the virus now being
discovered in most counties - the cemeteries division said
anti-mosquito steps should be taken by cemeteries throughout New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Besides making sure no stagnant water is allowed to stand in
monuments or elsewhere on cemetery grounds, the division is also
urging that only artificial or dried flowers be used to adorn
gravesites so that flower pots with water will not proliferate in
graveyards. It also recommended that people only visit cemeteries
during daylight hours, when mosquitoes are less active, and that
they wear proper clothing and use insect repellant.
</P>
<P>
   The administrator of the historic Oakwood Cemetery in Troy, near
Albany, said Monday he is unaware of any directive from the
cemeteries division warning against stagnant water and West
Nile-mosquito breeding grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Vogel said his cemetery has few water monuments like
fountains or pools, but people do frequently mark gravesites with
flowerpots with water in them.
</P>
<P>
   Among others buried at Oakwood are Civil War Gen. George Thomas,
the industrialist and humanitarian Russell Sage and Sam Wilson, the
Troy meatpacker whose supplies were thought to have initiated the
nickname ''Uncle Sam'' for the American government during the War
of 1812.
</P>
<P>
   The cemeteries division regulates non-denominational,
not-for-profit cemeteries in New York state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
