<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demand for food aid growing after welfare reform  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Stephanie Smith placed her nursing
textbook down on a table at House of Bread Monday afternoon and ate
a bologna sandwich, peas, carrots and macaroni salad.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm hungry,'' said Smith, 45, who is completing a 13-week
course to become a certified nurses' aide, hoping to earn more
money than she does working as a home health aide.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the mother of two daughters ages 11 and 27, was among
more than 230 people who came to the soup kitchen for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is outrageous today,'' said Rick Riccitelli, client
advocate. ''All of a sudden we have this crunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the state, soup kitchens, food pantries and shelters are
seeing longer lines as welfare reform leaves women with jobs that
don't pay enough to feed their families and more people live longer
on fixed incomes.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a real problem,'' said Rep. Jack Thompson,
D-Manchester. Being among the poorest in the nation's richest state
is a growing concern, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question that among families with young children
the incidents of poverty have increased,'' Thompson said. ''What
we're (also) learning is that more elderly people are using food
services.''
</P>
<P>
   From October 1996 to October 1999, food stamp participation
dropped 22 percent in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Many people are unaware that the program is for low-income,
working families, not welfare recipients, said Deidra Ierardi,
director of the Connecticut Association for Human Services'
anti-hunger coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ''The elderly also don't apply for food stamps out of pride,''
said Ierardi.
</P>
<P>
   The Meals on Wheels Program of Stamford/Darien Inc. has seen
about a 12 percent growth in clients over last year, now serving
about 130 meals each weekday and 165 on Saturdays and Sundays, said
Grace Mall, executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're serving more people now than ever before,'' said Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Daniels, 77, started coming to House of Bread a few
months ago. On Monday, she ate baked chicken, string beans and
''plenty of cranberry sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, a great-grandmother, retired from her job as a
housekeeper about 10 years ago to care for her terminally ill
daughter. Friends told her about the soup kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ''People should thank the lord for the food they get,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Food Bank Inc. of East Haven, which now serves 535
programs in New Haven, New London, Windham, Middlesex, Fairfield
and Litchfield counties, is seeing about a 10 percent growth in
food distribution this year, said executive director Nancy
Carrington.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the agency distributed about 7.3 million pounds of
food, compared with about 6.5 million pounds in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Salvation Army's Hartford Temple in the Frog Hollow
neighborhood distributes bags of food containing one- or two-week
supplies of groceries to 15 to 20 people, four days a week, said
Yazmin Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's mostly families with small children,'' she said. ''It's
very hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
