<HEADLINE> Palestinians Discuss Statehood Date  </HEADLINE>
By SARAH EL-DEEB
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- The Palestinians are trying to determine
when is the best time to declare statehood, Egypt's foreign
minister said Monday after a day of intensive Middle East
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat shuttled to Egypt for talks
with President Hosni Mubarak before returning home, where he is to
meet later with U.S. envoy Dennis Ross, who is trying to push ahead
talks after last month's failed Israeli-Palestinian peace summit.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said the Palestinians
were working on when to declare a state -- a move Arafat had earlier
set for Sept. 13 but he has since said he was reconsidering the
date. The United States and Israel have warned him against the
move.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is absolutely no change concerning the state or
Jerusalem, but the date of declaration is still subject to
discussion,'' Moussa told journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Syria's foreign minister met Mubarak in the
Mediterranean city of Alexandria and demanded Israel hand over to
the Palestinians all of east Jerusalem -- the main issue that
wrecked the July Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Farouk Al-Sharaa called on Israel to make ''a
complete withdrawal'' from east Jerusalem, saying it was an
integral part of occupied Arab territories. ''The issue in our view
requires a firm and principle-based position and does not need a
great deal of beating about the bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak had reportedly
offered the Palestinians limited control over parts of
traditionally Arab east Jerusalem. The Palestinians rejected the
offer, demanding that the entire area, which includes sites holy to
Muslims, Christians and Jews, must be under full Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan, King Abdullah prepared to visit Israel on Tuesday to
meet with Barak, following up talks the two leaders held in Amman
last week. In the earlier talks, Abdullah had rejected any Israeli
sovereignty over Muslim holy sites in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Moussa said Mubarak and al-Sharaa had focused on how to
coordinate Arab positions concerning the Middle East peace process.
Syria's new president, Bashar Assad, begins on Saturday his first
visits in the region with trips to Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations broke off in January because
of differences over what land would be included in an Israeli
withdraw from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak, a key regional peace mediator, has warned that a
collapse in Middle East peace talks could lead to renewed violence
in the region. He is due to meet with Israel's acting foreign
minister, Sholomo Ben-Ami, later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian Foreign Ministry officials say they are working with
the Palestinians to develop a plan for Jerusalem that will be
submitted to the United States and Israel. They declined to reveal
any details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 1617 </TRAILER>
