<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commissioner: Water is safe at Washington, other county fairs  </HEADLINE>
By REAGAN HAYNES
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, N.Y. (AP) - The state's health commissioner gulped
down a glass of water at the opening of the Washington County Fair
Monday and promised that last year's E. coli tragedy need not be a
worry.
</P>
<P>
   ''That water was good,'' Dr. Antonia Novello told Mike Grottoli,
whose maple sugar candy booth provided the commissioner with the
drink.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important thing ... is that we've gotten together and
converted something from a tragedy into positive change,'' Novello
said of changes implemented for all fair water systems in New York
since last year's outbreak, the worst in state history.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-year-old girl and an elderly man died and an estimated 1,000
people were sickened after drinking fair water that had been
contaminated with E. coli. The exact source of the contamination in
fairgrounds well water was not determined, but it was suspected
that it either originated from cow manure leaching into the ground
or from a leaking septic system in a fairground dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Novello required all fairgrounds in New York state
without access to a public water supply to chlorinate or otherwise
disinfect their water systems before holding public events.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Washington County Fair operators dug two new wells and
permanently sealed all but one of eight old wells, Washington
County Fair spokesman Pete Gregg said. The old well is only being
kept operable for fire emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said the treatment systems for the new wells, located at
opposite ends of the fairgrounds, include regular chlorinations and
''microfilters,'' which screen out microorganisms not killed by
chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   Water will be tested three times a day for the seven days of the
fair, Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington County Board of Supervisors Chairman Don Cummings
said his wife was hospitalized for five days due to E. coli from
the fair last year. But on Monday, he urged people not to stay
away. His wife only missed the fair because she had recently
cracked her hip, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want you to listen to my voice when I am saying that she
shows no ill will toward this fair,'' Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara and Michael Bade said they returned to the fair this
year without any worries of contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it was an extremely isolated case that unfortunately
turned catastrophic,'' Michael Bade said, adding: ''We had no
problems last year and we don't anticipate any this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Janine Reuter said they brought bottled water for
their daughters, a 9-month-old and a 2-year-old they pushed in
strollers, because children are most succeptible to E. coli.
However, they said they were drinking fair water without worry.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the fair's been around for so long, and they've only had
one instance in 110 years, that's pretty good,'' Scott Reuter said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of lawsuits were brought against fair operators last
year by people sickened from E. coli in the fair water. The
lawsuits charge that operators were negligent for not properly
testing, chlorinating or treating the well water, and for locating
wells near barns.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Benjamin, attorney handling the cases, said in a
telephone interview that his clients are not upset that the
111-year-old fair continues.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tracey Weaver, whose father Ernest Walker died from the
E. coli contamination, said she thinks the fair should have been
canceled this year out of respect for her father.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver has filed a lawsuit against the fair. She said her
father's death continues to take a toll on her family.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the lawsuit,'' she said. ''I'd like someone from the
fair to call and say, 'We're sorry this happened.' Not one person
from Washington County called,'' Weaver told the Post-Star of Glens
Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Following the outbreak, Novello issued emergency orders
prohibiting the use of untreated water at seven agricultural
fairgrounds: Chenango County; Genesee County; Madison County;
Washington County; Wyoming County; Orleans County and and Tioga
County.
</P>
<P>
   Novello said Monday all fairs with wells have complied with a
state directive that their drinking water be treated with
anti-bacterial agents or have hooked up their systems to town water
supplies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
