<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Basque: Separatist Violence History  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL WOOLLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILBAO, Spain (AP) -- They are an ancient people who speak a
linguistic enigma. Through the centuries, they've mastered
everything from whaling to banking. Their most famous son is a
prominent saint.
</P>
<P>
   But the distinguished history of the Basque people includes an
undercurrent of separatist violence that has produced Europe's
longest-running regional conflict.
</P>
<P>
   This summer has been a terrifying one of bullets and exploding
cars: The Basque separatist group ETA has launched a nationwide
offensive, making a 14-month truce it halted in December seem like
a distant memory. The cease-fire ended after a round of stillborn
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven people have been killed since the cease-fire ended, and
since early July alone ETA has staged 14 attacks. But Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar, who survived an ETA car bombing in 1995,
has ruled out Basque independence or any other concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say ETA's latest spasm of violence is designed to show
that Aznar's policy is futile and to force him to go beyond the
current system, which grants the Basques broad autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may be that ETA is paving the way for a second truce in
more advantageous conditions than the first,'' political scientist
Ramon Cotarelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnaldo Otegi, leader of Euskal Herritarrok, a political party
linked to ETA, said Basques are just like any other people waging a
legitimate fight for sovereignty. He compared them to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why should we be any different?'' he asked a Bilbao rally
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Spaniards who welcomed the first cease-fire as a
breath of fresh air after decades of strife hunker down and wait
for the next gunshot or bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
   The tension is thick here in Bilbao, the largest and richest
city in the Basque region of northern Spain.
</P>
<P>
   A screech of tires is enough to make heads turn. When a stranger
with a parcel walks into a neighborhood tavern, the regulars stare
holes through him. People talk politics in whispers, if at all. You
never know who may be listening, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is madness,'' said Carlos Zabaleta, a 35-year-old engineer,
as he strolled through a park and watched his 2-year-old son, Ivan,
feed the ducks. ''We were all so happy with the cease-fire. And
now, here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake is one of Spain's most industrialized regions and one
of its most beautiful. Home to 2.1 million people, the three Basque
provinces run from the western end of the Pyrenees about 100 miles
across Spain's northern coast.
</P>
<P>
   The neighboring Navarra region to the south also has a large
Basque population, and just across the border in France are three
other Basque provinces. ETA is fighting to turn all seven into an
independent homeland called Euskadi.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish Basque provinces are a land of jagged green hills,
postcard-pretty hamlets and elegant seaside cities like San
Sebastian.
</P>
<P>
   Bilbao, a once-mighty steel and shipbuilding center, has
undergone a painful reconversion triggered by globalization. These
days it's best known abroad for the curvy silver walls of the
Guggenheim Museum, a resurgent city's pride and joy.
</P>
<P>
   The Basque country is also one of Spain's wealthiest regions,
with a per capita gross domestic product of $32,300 -- 22 percent
higher than Spain's national average.
</P>
<P>
   Basques were living where they do now long before King Ferdinand
and Queen Isabel fused their own and other lands of the Iberian
peninsula -- including Basque country -- in the early 16th century,
laying the foundation for what became Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Residing in quiet mountain reducts and speaking a language
called Euskera -- linguists say it's unrelated to any other
Indo-European tongue -- the Basques spent centuries battling,
tolerating or cutting deals with Romans, Visigoths, Moors and other
intruders.
</P>
<P>
   One Basque knight, wounded while fighting French invaders in
1521, underwent a spiritual awakening and founded the Society of
Jesus, the Roman Catholic order known as the Jesuits. Ignatius of
Loyola was canonized in 1621.
</P>
<P>
   ETA, which stands for Basque Homeland and Liberty, emerged in
the late 1960s when Spain was ruled by military dictator Francisco
Franco. He cracked down brutally on groups with distinct languages
and cultures, including the Basques.
</P>
<P>
   ETA is blamed for nearly 800 killings. One of the most
spectacular came on Dec. 20, 1973, when -- after spending weeks
tunneling under a street in one of Madrid's poshest neighborhoods --
commandos detonated a bomb just as a car drove by carrying Luis
Carrero Blanco, Franco's second in command and widely expected
successor. The blast was so thunderous the car ended up on top of a
building, and Blanco was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Under Franco's repressive rule, ETA may have enjoyed at least
the sympathies of non-Basques, if not their support. But Franco
died in 1975, Spain is now a prosperous, stable democracy and the
Basque region has much say in running its own affairs. Most
Spaniards see ETA not as a national liberation group, but as a gang
of terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   People in the Basque region itself are divided roughly in half
between those backing mainstream status-quo parties and supporters
of Basque nationalist parties. And many Spaniards take pains not to
lump all Basques together: A standard slogan at anti-ETA rallies is
''Basques, yes. ETA, no.''
</P>
<P>
   But there has been across-the-board fury over the recent
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone lines to radio talk shows are jammed with people in
tears, proposing everything from severing the Basque country from
the rest of Spain and setting it afloat in the Bay of Biscay to
calling a binding referendum on its future. Many of the talk show
calls urge fearful people living in Basque country to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''Come join us in the rest of Spain,'' said one caller. ''We'll
set another place at the table.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 1642 </TRAILER>
