<DOCNO> APW20000821.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cold shoulders: Record lows hit parts of the Northeast  </HEADLINE>
By GREG SUKIENNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) - Summer is giving people the cold shoulder in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Record or near-record low temperatures have been reported in
cities across the region, spurring some people to dig into their
fall wardrobes early and turn the heat on.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Avery was surprised to get nearly a dozen calls from
customers Monday asking to have heating systems installed. He got
only one call about air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ''Typically, people don't start thinking about that until they
have to, in September,'' said Avery, president of Avery Services
Inc. in Westbrook, Maine. ''I don't doubt that it was so chilly
this morning that it got people thinking a month early about
winter.''
</P>
<P>
   The mercury dropped to 43 in Wilkes-Barre, Pa., on Monday
morning, tying a record low for the date set in 1908. At Bradley
International Airport near Hartford, Conn., the temperature hit 45,
matching a record low set in 1984. Elmira, N.Y., hit a statewide
low of 37 degrees early Monday. And low temperatures across
northern New England hovered in 40s over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, the early-morning chill had employees at Killington
Resort joking about making snow in August. It's nearly cold enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been in the low 40s and upper 30s on the mountain,'' said
Amy Phalon, a spokeswoman for Killington.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Farmer, co-owner of Farmers Garden Center in Elmira, N.Y.,
said the cool weather is keeping corn and other vegetables from
ripening.
</P>
<P>
   ''Corn needs hot, muggy nights,'' she said. ''People growing
tomatoes in the gardens are having trouble. Everyone is loading up
on green tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   The cool weather is no problem for crops such as beets, lettuce
and leeks, said Rich Bananno of Methuen, a past president of the
New England Vegetable and Berry Growers Association. What's more,
''it's fine weather to work in.''
</P>
<P>
   The cooler weather has decreased demand for electricity in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, there had been at least 10 days when
demand rose above 21,000 megawatts; this summer, that has happened
only five times, said Ellen Foley of ISO New England, which
oversees the region's power grid.
</P>
<P>
   The cooler weather has made it tough for those who make their
livelihood off summer cruises. Massachusetts Bay Lines has seen
ridership on its whale watch cruises dip along with the
temperature, which is usually about 10 degrees cooler at sea than
it is on land.
</P>
<P>
   ''Public cruises are down 35 percent,'' said Shane Lemay, the
cruise line's marketing manager. ''There's been a lot of northeast
wind. That kicks up a lot of spray and makes the seas rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the temperatures neared 70 at midday in Boston, some
people still chose to dress warmly. Molly Bronitsky wore a cardigan
sweater as she walked along Boston Common.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like it a little warmer,'' she said. ''It's good
weather for September, but for right now it's cold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-21-00 1651 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000821.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright, CIA Discuss Declassifying  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright talked
with CIA Director George Tenet on Monday about the prospective
release of thousands of secret documents on activities of South
American military dictatorships in power near the close of the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said a conflict has arisen at the CIA
over whether to release a small number of documents pertaining to
the 17-year rule of Chilean President Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   The question of secret U.S. documents was a centerpiece of
Albright's visit to Argentina and Chile last week.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has set a Sept. 14 deadline for release of
documents. Human rights groups in Argentina and Chile want the
material to shed additional light on abuses committed by the
Pinochet government, which ruled from 1973-1990, and military
governments that ruled Argentina from 1976-83.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the United States wants to be ''as helpful as
possible'' in shedding light on that grim period in both countries.
She briefed Tenet on her discussions in the two countries, where
some activists doubt that the United States will release all
relevant documents.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Monday the goal
is ''the maximum possible release of documents consistent with the
need to protect sources and methods.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official, who asked not to be identified, said the
conflict at the Central Intelligence Agency concerns the release of
about 20 documents that some officials contend should be released
and others that they remain classified to protect information on
sources and methods.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to declassify documents on a mass scale was made by
President Clinton last year. A substantial amount of material was
released in two stages last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 1658 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
