<DOCNO> APW20000821.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BPU takes comments on how to ensure utilities for needy households  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - With electric and gas service no longer
operating as monopolies in New Jersey, the question remains on how
to provide heat and light to needy households.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities and citizens' groups provided a number of answers
Monday to the state Board of Public Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The BPU has the task of determining how a ''Universal Service
Fund'' should operate, according to the state's deregulation law
enacted in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the board heard a variety of suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the state's largest utility, Public Service
Electric &AMP; Gas Co., wants the fund to be part of an existing state
agency and ''serve as an umbrella or clearinghouse of energy
assistance programs for the needy to help them meet essential
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The company ''emphasizes that the public utilities and
ratepayers of this state should not be held responsible for
providing permanent or pervasive financial assistance to consumers
who are in a chronic or pervasive situation that requires such
assistance,'' PSE&AMP;G rate counsel Frances I. Sundheim said in
written comments to the board.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Retired Persons, however, suggested
that ratepayers foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   AARP contended the cost would be largely covered by the money
utilities would save by reducing debt-collection efforts and the
130,000 annual shut-off of electric and gas service to people who
have not paid their bills.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Fair Share Payment Plan'' proposed by AARP requires
families to pay a percentage of their monthly income toward their
utility bill and it covers the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Like a plan suggested by the state's ratepayer advocate, it
forgives existing debt owed by poor customers.
</P>
<P>
   The advocate, Blossom A. Peretz, suggests a fund that assists
households with incomes at or below 150 percent of the federal
poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   The advocate's consultant on universal service, Roger Colton,
told the BPU that the three energy assistance programs now
available to New Jersey residents do not address the affordability
of service.
</P>
<P>
   The existing programs include the federal Low-Income Home Energy
Assistance Program, which provides aid for heating. Last winter, it
provided aid to 50,000 of the 400,000 low-income utility customers
in New Jersey, Colton said.
</P>
<P>
   The BPU will hear further comment 7 p.m. Tuesday at the
Jamesburg Municipal Building.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Board of Public Utilities:
http://www.state.nj.us/bpu
</P>
<P>
   Ratepayer advocate: http://www.njin.net/rpa
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
