<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More than 300 people apply to FEMA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SPARTA, N.J. (AP) - The Federal Emergency Management Agency has
received more than 350 applications for assistance from residents
and businesses damaged by last week's flooding in northwestern New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA, which set up an office in Sparta over the weekend, will
probably start distributing some grants in a few days, spokesman
Mike Beeman said. But he cautioned residents not to expect a grant
to replace everything they have lost.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a high expectation and hope from the people that the
federal government's going to come in and make them whole and pay
for what they lost,'' Beeman said. ''That's what insurance
companies are for.''
</P>
<P>
   The average FEMA grant to New Jersey victims of Tropical Storm
Floyd, which caused much more damage in the state, was $2,900,
Beeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the applicants who called FEMA's toll-free numbers were
in between Sparta and Stanhope in Stanhope in Sussex County, with
others in Jefferson Township in Morris County, Beeman said.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA officials inspected many homes over the weekend, mostly
finding waterlogged basements and damage outside the home, Beeman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sussex County officials have begun restoration work on one of
four bridges deemed critical because they cut off isolated
populations, County Emergency Management Director Skip Danielson
said. Construction on the Morris Lake bridge in Sparta began last
week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Danielson said most people have returned to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's two dozen, I'd be surprised,'' he said of people who
still haven't returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
