<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Colombian kingpin faces U.S. drug charges  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A man identified as one of Colombia's most
powerful drug lords was hauled into a U.S. court for the first time
Monday to face cocaine-trafficking charges carrying a possible life
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Orlandez Gamboa had arrived in New York under tight
security Saturday after Colombian President Andres Pastrana and his
cabinet approved his extradition, despite death threats by drug
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, the short,
balding Gamboa, 44, sat impassively as prosecutors portrayed him as
the mastermind of a decade-long international scheme to smuggle an
estimated eight tons of cocaine worth more than a billion dollars.
They alleged that he continued to run his ring from behind bars in
Colombia, where he was arrested in 1998 on murder and kidnapping
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Magistrate Frank Maas ordered Gamboa held without bail until
Thursday, when he was expected to enter a plea. He faces 10 years
to life in prison if convicted on federal conspiracy, drug
smuggling and money laundering charges.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Gamboa told reporters their client was a
''legitimate businessman'' who ran taxi and bus companies in
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is simply not guilty,'' attorney Martin Schmuckler said
outside court.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Gamboa, nicknamed ''Caracol'' - Spanish for
''The Snail'' - is the first drug kingpin to be extradited to the
United States since Colombia lifted its ban on extradition in 1997.
Pastrana supports extraditing accused drug traffickers to the
United States, where stiffer penalties often await them.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White thanked
Colombian officials for their ''courage and cooperation'' in making
Gamboa ''face American justice for his alleged crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa's extradition comes one week after a band of drug dealers
in Colombia took out a newspaper ad threatening to assassinate
supreme court judges and government officials there unless they
reversed their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''We won't allow the immoral American drug addicts to try us,''
said the ad, published in Cali, a city located 185 miles from
Bogota, in drug-producing southern Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The group behind the threats claimed to be an offshoot of the
notorious 1980s drug-financed terrorist faction ''The
Un-extraditables.''
</P>
<P>
   According to an indictment filed in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan last year, Gamboa's ''Caracol Organization'' smuggled
cocaine into the United States through Puerto Rico and other
Caribbean points. Since 1996, federal agents have intercepted
thousands of kilos in New York City, Philadelphia and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The cocaine often was packaged in sawdust, mustard and cough
medicine to try to hide the drugs' odor, authorities said. It then
was shipped in crates with corn oil, engine parts and bananas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
