<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NJ--Civil War Letters, Bjt,620  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODBURY, N.J. (AP) - Homesick, scared and dejected while
fighting in the Civil War, Second Lt. Benjamin F. Young wrote
letters describing the bloodshed and his thoughts to his niece,
Lizzie Brick, in Hurffville.
</P>
<P>
   ''I often set in my lowly tent and reflect on my past life and I
like many others can point to actions which I would gladly have
wiped out,'' he wrote on Nov. 26, 1862. ''I have stood on the field
of battle and seen death being hurled in all directions. I seen my
fellow comrades fall by my side and their blood sprinkled over me.
I seen some crippled for life some killed instantly. others calling
on their freinds in their dieing moments with agony and great
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Yellowed and brittle, Young's letters and those of dozens of
other soldiers have been preserved under protective coverings in
special boxes in a vault at the Gloucester County Historical
Society here.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the help of an $11,000 State Library grant, the 202
letters are being copied onto microfilm and also transcribed.
Copies will be stored in the New Jersey State Library and the State
Archives in Trenton and at the Gloucester County Historical Society
in Woodbury. By next year, they will be available for researchers
across the country through interlibrary loans.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Niederer, director of the State Archives, said the
microfilmed letters will be stored in a climate-controlled, secure
vault.
</P>
<P>
   He said the letters and diaries of Civil War soldiers have
proven to be valuable for research by scholars and by those
studying local history.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the letters were sent to Lizzie Brick, a faithful pen
pal to several of her relatives and friends at war. One of Brick's
descendants gave her letters to the Historical Society, said Edith
Hoelle, library director.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were probably in someone's attic in a trunk someplace,''
Hoelle said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have stood on the very brink of death,'' Young, who was in
the 56th Regiment of the Pennsylvania Volunteers, wrote to his
niece, ''yet God in his mercy has spared me through all. and why is
it so is a question which often occurs in my mind. It is a mystery
I cannot solve. it must be because you and others who love me
intercedes in my behalf when you send up your humble prayers to him
who does all for the best. ... Oh how i wish this horrid war was
over ... there has been enough bloodshed already by far too much.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13, 1863, Young wrote: ''Dear neice, When I returned to
my regiment I found many of my former comrades missing, our
regiment now numbers 72 men, my company has only 6 men in it. Oh
Lizzie only think that about two years ago we came out with over
900 men and they have dwindled down to seventy two. Two thirds of
the missing have been killed or crippled for life it is awful to
think of have I not reason to be thankful for my good luck,
sometimes I think my guardian angel must hover close around me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas D. Clark wrote to Brick from a camp near Falmouth, Va.,
on March 20, 1863:
</P>
<P>
   ''Friend Lizzie, I now take the present opertunity to write you
a fiew lines. Hopeing they will find you well. ... I received your
welcom letter and was very glad to har from you &AMP; to hear that you
are a Solger's friend and like to hear from them. I know there is
folks at home that never thinks of Poor Solger. ...
</P>
<P>
   I think we are fighting for a good cos &AMP; that cos is to montane
one of the Best Governments thats in whole world. ... I don't think
the day is far off when Pees will be declared &AMP; the old Stars &AMP;
Stripes will Proudly wave over our land &AMP; nation one mor.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.state.nj.us/statelibrary/admin.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
