<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge orders prison's mental health reports made public  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Progress reports from an outside doctor
hired to review the state's treatment of mentally ill prisoners
should be made public, a federal judge ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Humane treatment of prisoners is a public concern, and the only
way for the public to ensure that interest is to have access to
such reports, the judge said in his 36-page opinion.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials agreed to keep the reports secret after
settling a lawsuit last year. An advocacy group claimed mentally
ill prison inmates were poorly treated and subjected to abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch went to court claiming it had a right to know
how these prisoners were being treated.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only way for the public to know of the state of affairs of
our prisons is to have access to documents that chronicle both the
prison system's deficiencies and improvements,'' wrote U.S.
Magistrate Judge John Hughes
</P>
<P>
   ''Moreover, it is important that entities, both public and
private, doing the government's business be held accountable for
their actions, and answer to its citizenry, whose taxpaying dollars
support the prison establishments,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch plans to include these reports in its review
of prison conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to look at the before and after. At least now we'll
know what the 'before' is from these reports,'' said Bruce Rosen, a
lawyer representing Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully now some of this information will become
available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office plans no appeal, said spokesman
Paul Loriquet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will obviously comply with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state is pleased that the judge allowed for some changes in
the expert reports before they are made public, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections department officials can withhold inmates names to
protect the privacy of their medical treatment, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   The original lawsuit was filed by the Inmate Advocacy Clinic at
Seton Hall University Law School, which sought better treatment for
mentally ill state prison inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners whose illnesses caused outbursts or other behavioral
problems were disciplined, not treated, the lawsuit alleged.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials last year agreed to almost all demands in
the lawsuit, promising changes at every level in the system
treating mentally ill inmates. The Department of Corrections said
it would hire more staff, offer better training, build treatment
facilities and rewrite disciplinary procedures to consider an
inmate's illness.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said a forensic psychiatrist would visit state
prisons four times a year, interview inmates and review procedures.
According to court documents, his reports determine if the state is
complying with the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman administration paid $16 million this year for
improvements ordered by the settlement and budgeted $17.7 million
for the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the inmates' condition is more and more improved, then
these reports will show that,'' Rosen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
