<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 33; Nasdaq Gains 23  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed higher Monday on optimism that the
Federal Reserve Board will leave interest rates alone Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 33.33 at 11,079.81.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 7.76 at 1,499.48, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 22.81 at 3,953.15.
</P>
<P>
   Trading has been light during recent sessions as traders look
ahead to Tuesday's Federal Reserve meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said most investors stayed on the sidelines Monday, not
willing to gamble one way or the other on whether the Fed will
increase rates or leave them stable.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, conventional wisdom holds that the Fed is finished
with its credit-tightening campaign and will leave interest rates
alone for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what's been driving the markets for the past three
weeks,'' said Jack Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at
Advest Inc. ''The market is pretty much convinced that the Fed will
do nothing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates six times in the past 14
months in an effort to slow the economy and stave off inflation.
The strategy appears to be working, as a number of economic
indicators released in recent weeks have signaled that the economy
is still growing but inflation hasn't reached dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
   Shaughnessy said Fed policy makers set out last summer to fix an
economic imbalance in which demand for products had outstripped
productivity. But productivity growth soared in the second quarter
of 2000 versus the first, while consumer demand has eased, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Fed has achieved their goals of a soft economic landing
with stable growth and low inflation,'' Shaughnessy added.
</P>
<P>
   Technology issues, led by chip maker Intel, extended a rally
Monday that began last week.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's shares rose $1.50 to $72.063 after an analyst raised his
future earnings forecasts for the number one maker of computer
chips. The analyst said Intel's third quarter inventory is already
sold out, news that bodes well for the entire computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications parts makers also remained strong, following
up on last week's gains. Ciena Corp. rose $5.375 to $182.063, and
Copper Mountain was up $5.313 to $69.313.
</P>
<P>
   And Clearnet Communications, which operates a digital telecom
network, rose $13 to $44 after Canadian phone company Telus Corp.
agreed to buy the wireless service provider for $4.48 billion in
cash, stock and assumed debt. The announcement boosted wireless
stocks across the board.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sector continued to show weakness on fears that
second-half profits may be hurt by the cooling economy. Dow
component Wal-mart Stores was down $1.437 at $49.063.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation stocks were also hammered, falling on the ongoing
woes of the airline industry, which announced a summit meeting to
discuss delays that have plagued air travelers all summer. UAL
Corp., parent of United Airlines, fell 93.70 cents to $48.938.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 909.04 million
shares, well below Friday's pace of 993 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.94 at 516.45.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.5 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 0.5 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 0.02 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
