<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Finds AWOL U.S. Army Officer  </HEADLINE>
By JASMINA KELEMEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETAH TIKVA, Israel (AP) -- A U.S. Army Reserve intelligence
officer AWOL from his base in Texas turned up Monday at a youth
hostel in Israel, where police said they were talking to him but
had no plans to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Jeremiah Mattysse was picked up by plainclothes police
in Mitzpeh Ramon, a desert town famed for its crater and its hippie
culture, and brought to Israel's international crimes unit in Petah
Tivka, near Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   American military officials said they're especially concerned
about Mattysse's absence because of his background in U.S.
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Hanley, a spokesman for the U.S. Army Reserve Command in
Atlanta, said last week that it would be logical for an
investigation to include ensuring that nothing was missing from
offices where Mattysse worked.
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse smiled as he got into the car Monday, wearing the
knitted skullcap typical of Orthodox Jews and a T-shirt with a
floral motif.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to ''review the case,'' a police statement said.
Israeli law has no provision for arresting someone who deserts a
foreign army, and Mattysse could leave the station when he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Late into a session that stretched over two hours, U.S.
diplomats joined the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Until February, Mattysse commanded the Army Reserve Intelligence
Support Center at Camp Bullis in San Antonio, Texas, as a full-time
reserve officer. The unit's primary mission was to train reservists
in intelligence work.
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse, 50, failed to report to duty on Aug. 8 after a
vacation, making him AWOL, or absent without leave.
</P>
<P>
   Mattysse had been reassigned to the 90th Reserve Support Group
in San Antonio after an investigation began into his wife's
allegations that he had an extramarital affair. The San Antonio
Express-News reported that his wife, Vanda Mattysse, filed a
divorce complaint March 7 in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Rivka Artzi-Nir, a woman who lives in Israel and identified
herself as Mattysse's girlfriend, has told Israeli newspapers he
had become devoted to helping Israel since he converted to Judaism
10 years ago. Artzi-Nir staked out the police station, carrying
religious instruction books she said Mattysse would want for
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Artzi-Nir, 48, has said Mattysse sent her classified material
through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Mattysse case has drawn widespread public attention. Yoram
Sheftel, best-known for successfully defending Cleveland autoworker
John Demjanjuk against charges he committed crimes against humanity
while serving as a World War II concentration camp guard, said he
was ready to defend Mattysse and accused police of kowtowing to
American interests.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kleiner, a right-wing legislator, also turned up at the
police station and compared Mattysse to Jonathan Pollard, the U.S.
intelligence analyst sentenced sentence to life in prison in the
United States for giving secret documents to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want another Pollard case,'' Kleiner said. ''Hundreds
of Israeli soldiers are in the United States who fled the army, no
one arrested them. We're not a banana republic, but we're acting
like one.''
</P>
<P>
   The police could deport Mattysse once his tourist visa runs out
-- such visas are usually issued for three to six months -- but, as a
Jew, Mattysse would be eligible for automatic citizenship. Interior
Ministry officials said Mattysse has asked to immigrate to Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 1812 </TRAILER>
