<HEADLINE> Turnpike troopers trained as emergency technicians  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOORESTOWN, N.J. (AP) - The next New Jersey State Police trooper
to pull you over may also be able to perform lifesaving first aid.
</P>
<P>
   Three troopers assigned to Moorestown have been trained as
emergency medical technicians as part of a pilot program to equip
police to respond to medical emergencies on the New Jersey
Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ''The effort is geared to save lives by allowing the trooper to
offer more than just first aid to seriously injured motorists and
turnpike visitors,'' State Police Superintendent Col. Carson J.
Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers I. Frank Babinchock, Joseph Shanahan and Louis Bucchere
have completed courses to learn how to administer CPR and treat
people injured in car accidents, suffering from heart attacks,
choking, respiratory failure, epileptic seizures, drowning, burns
and other injuries, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The program, funded by the New Jersey Turnpike Authority,
includes three specially marked patrol vehicles equipped with
defibrillators and emergency medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the three troopers will still notify emergency
medical teams and ambulances to come to accident scenes, but may be
able to stabilize the injured until other emergency medical help
arrives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
