<DOCNO> APW20000821.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki signs pesticide neighbor notification law  </HEADLINE>
By PAT MILTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYOSSET, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki on Monday signed the
nation's first law aimed at protecting New York residents against
possible harmful effects of pesticide spraying by neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires companies that use pesticides to give at least
a 48-hour warning to neighbors living within 150 feet of any
spraying site. It also requires schools and day care facilities to
provide parents and staff with a notice before pesticides are
applied on school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every neighbor will now know to take in the wash, close the
windows, and not have the kids roll around in the yard,'' Pataki
said at the bill signing ceremony in the Willets Elementary school
yard.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was first suggested by Neal Lewis, head of the
Nassau-Suffolk Neighborhood Network. In 1992, Lewis heard about a
woman whose child suffered an allergic reaction to spraying at a
neighboring home.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Nicole Hudson of Farmingville, was gardening when she
saw a worker spraying trees in the neighbor's yard.
</P>
<P>
   As a white cloud with a noxious odor floated toward an open
bedroom of her house where her newborn slept, she called over to
the worker who was clad in protective gear. ''Don't worry about it
lady, I'm done already,'' he yelled back.
</P>
<P>
   In horror, she raced upstairs to find her baby, who was crying.
The child was later treated for the allergic reaction to a toxic
chemical. Hudson was instructed to destroy the linens and other
belongings in the baby's room.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great victory for the health and safety of our
residents,'' Lewis said, adding that support from Long Island's
breast cancer action groups and other environmental organizations
statewide boosted the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor notification law goes into effect March 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Notices must contain information regarding the date and location
of applications and the name of the product being applied. The law
allows exemptions for more than 30 specific types of pesticides
with a low toxicity, such as boric acid and horticultural oils, and
for pesticide applications to cemeteries and spot treatments of
less than nine square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said at least seven states allow residents to register
with the state if they want to be notified about pesticide spraying
near their home. But he said that New York is the first to require
residents of adjacent properties to be warned ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that this bill will set the standard for states
throughout the country,'' said State Sen. Carl Marcellino
(R-Plainview), who co-sponsored the bill with Assemblyman Tom
DiNapoli (D-Thomaston).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-21-00 1846 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000821.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Virginia still faces horseshoe crab moratorium  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW BARAKAT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) - An interstate fishing commission on
Monday failed to recommend a reprieve for Virginia from a pending
moratorium on horseshoe crab fishing.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Pruitt, Virginia's representative to the Atlantic
States Marine Fisheries Commission, said he remains optimistic the
feds will postpone the moratorium, scheduled to take effect in
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   If no reprieve is granted, Virginia will sue to stop the
sanction, Pruitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, a 15-state compact sanctioned by Congress to
regulate Atlantic fishing, has required all states to cut back
harvests of horseshoe crabs, a 350 million-year-old evolutionary
oddity that plays a key role in the East Coast ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Migratory birds feed on horseshoe crab eggs. Conch fishermen use
horseshoe crabs as bait. And the biomedical industry uses horseshoe
crab blood to produce a product that's used to test drugs and
medical devices.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that horseshoe crabs have been overfished in recent
years, the commission ordered Virginia to cut its quota from
710,000 crabs to 152,495. Similar cutbacks were imposed on other
states.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia is the only state to reject the quotas. In July,
the Virginia Marine Resources Commission cut its quota in half to
355,000, but says further cuts are not warranted scientifically and
would harm the states $7 million conch fishing industry, the
largest of any Atlantic state.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is all being done for political reasons. That's the
reality,'' said Jack Travelstead, a VRMC member.
</P>
<P>
   ''The livelihoods of Virginia's conch fishermen hang in the
balance here,'' said Pruitt, also a VMRC member.
</P>
<P>
   At Virginia's urging, the commission agreed to review a proposal
to allow states that don't fill their quota to transfer the
difference to states that need it.
</P>
<P>
   Travelstead said Virginia could easily comply with the
commission's order if such quota transfers were permitted, although
he did not cite any states that would be willing to transfer their
allotments to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Pruitt said the idea of quota transfers was warmly received by
the Department of Commerce in a recent meeting. He expects the
department, which has final authority on the issue, to delay the
moratorium until the commission can review the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Perra, who represented the federal government at
Monday's meeting, said there's no reason to postpone the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point I don't see a reason to change course,'' Perra
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Plumart, a policy adviser with the National Audubon
Society, said Virginia is ''still in open defiance of the plan''
agreed to by the other states.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, the commission recommended a five-year time
limit on a pending safe harbor zone for horseshoe crabs in a
30-mile radius around the mouth of Delaware Bay, the creature's
prime spawning ground.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission:
http://www.asmfc.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
