<HEADLINE> Liberty Buys Into Game Show Network  </HEADLINE>
By GARY GENTILE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Liberty Digital Inc., the new media unit of
AT&AMP;T's Liberty Media Group, will take a 50 percent stake in Sony
Picture Entertainment's Game Show Network. The stock and cash deal
is valued at $275 million.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies will create a 24-hour interactive games
network using interactive television technology to allow viewers to
play along with game shows using their computers or set-top boxes,
such as Microsoft Corp.'s WebTV.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty has been taking stakes in a variety of technology and
content companies as it prepares to deliver programming to AT&AMP;T's
cable subscribers. In 1998, Liberty Media and Sony Pictures
Entertainment entered into a 50-50 partnership to buy the
Spanish-language network Telemundo.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fleming, president of the Game Show Network, said the
Telemundo deal began a series of discussions between Sony and
Liberty on future partnerships that led to Monday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty will buy its stake with $225 million in cash and $50
million in Liberty Digital stock. The deal is expected to close in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounds like a strong deal for them,'' said James Penhume,
an analyst at The Yankee Group. ''They're assembling the components
for what is likely to be the interactive television offering on
AT&AMP;T's cable system.''
</P>
<P>
   Penhume said the value of offering games on interactive
television is that it gets people acclimated to the blend of
television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are applications consumers really understand and see
through quickly,'' he said. ''They're easy and fun. Then you can
work your way up to the other stuff,'' including making purchases
using a remote control or wireless keypad.
</P>
<P>
   ''Games are intrinsically interactive,'' said Fleming. ''It
doesn't take a lot of explanation to get consumers to
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Game Show Network is seen by 29 million cable and satellite
television subscribers. It runs classic television game shows,
including episodes of ''What's My Line,'' ''Beat The Clock'' and
''Match Game.''
</P>
<P>
   The network already airs one interactive game show. Viewers of
''Inquizition'' can play along in real time using a telephone or on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The technology works in the same way as the ''enhanced
television'' version of ''Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' which
airs on the ABC Television Network.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.gameshownetwork.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
