<HEADLINE> U.S. Retaliates for Diplomat Expel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States ordered the expulsion of two
Congolese diplomats Monday in retaliation for Congo's decision to
expel two American diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said the two
diplomats must leave the country by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have taken this step reluctantly, but the Congolese
government's unjustified expulsion of two American diplomats left
us with no choice,'' Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official, asking not to be identified, said
the Congolese are minister counselor Nestor B. Wawa and political
counselor Paul Ruhamya Chikaza.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Congo ordered press officer Denise Burgess and
political counselor Roger James Moran to leave for making
statements it contended were inconsistent with their diplomatic
role.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said the two have since returned to Washington. U.S.
Ambassador William Swing called Congolese President Laurent Kabila
on Saturday to protest the expulsions.
</P>
<P>
   Congolese officials said the two were ordered home for
objectionable statements made to civil society leaders at a
diplomatic function.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher had no comment on the precise nature of the statements
except that some allegations by Congolese officials were
''outrageous and false.''
</P>
<P>
   He reaffirmed the State Department's complete confidence in the
''professionalism, integrity and prudence'' of the two U.S.
officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
