<DOCNO> APW20000821.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi's President Warns Tutsis  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYNE SAMBIRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- In a remarkable admission of
vulnerability, Burundi's President Pierre Buyoya warned opponents
Monday not to attempt a coup ahead of talks aimed at ending his
country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya, a Tutsi, apparently directed his warning at radical
Tutsi opposition parties that are behind recent anti-government
protests. He is scheduled to meet this weekend in South Africa with
Nelson Mandela, the former South African president and mediator in
talks aimed at settling Burundi's seven-year civil war with Hutu
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who want to overthrow the government so that the
president will not be there to sign the peace agreement should know
that their actions will come to no good,'' Buyoya told a meeting of
more than a thousand local administrators and civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Buyoya's request for a delay, Mandela wants to see the
power-sharing agreement that would establish ethnic balance in the
army, government and parliament signed Aug. 28. Tutsis, who
constitute a minority, dominate the military and government. The
Hutus are the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela has already invited President Clinton and other world
leaders to witness and support the agreement. On Saturday, Mandela
will go to the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha to prepare for the
signing, his office said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems as if the mediator (Mandela) is reluctant to postpone
the signing of a peace agreement,'' Buyoya said. If he doesn't
sign, Mandela will see it as ''a sign of disrespect'' and think
Burundians do not want peace, he added.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the agreement among Buyoya's government, Hutu
rebels and opposition parties would end a war that has killed at
least 200,000 people. Violence erupted after Tutsi paratroopers
assassinated Melchior Ndadaye, the first democratically elected
president and a Hutu, in October 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya, a retired army major, appealed Sunday for support from
the Army High Council, which put him in power in a 1996 coup, and
the Tutsi parties and interest groups negotiating in Arusha,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, Bujumbura, where middle-class Tutsis are
Buyoya's main constituency, protests are on the rise against
negotiations with leaders of the three Hutu factions, seen as
responsible for the killings of Tutsis. A declining economy adds to
the pressure on Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, 6,000 students at the University of Bujumbura, most
of them Tutsis, boycotted classes over the government's failure to
end the violence. Their lecturers, backed by a trade union, joined
the boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Grenades exploded in two suburbs where soldiers briefly clashed
with anti-government protesters.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after Buyoya delivered his speech, a huge fire
engulfed an open market at Jabe, burning wooden stalls and houses
in one of Bujumbura's busiest suburbs. The fire turned the night
sky orange over the unusually quiet capital. It was not clear,
however, what caused it.
</P>
<P>
   Police and soldiers set up checkpoints in the area and people
stayed indoors.
</P>
<P>
   The two main Hutu rebel groups link a cease-fire with the
closing of all ''regroupment camps,'' where the army had herded
some 350,000 Hutu civilians to separate them from rebels who depend
on them.
</P>
<P>
   The government says most of the camps have been closed under
international pressure and in spite of worsening security.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mandela asked United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan to send a three-person team to investigate camp closures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 1939 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000821.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lopez's 'Cell' Tops Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Movie-goers found a trip into a serial
killer's mind too appealing to pass up, giving Jennifer Lopez's
''The Cell'' a top box-office debut with $17.5 million over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez plays a psychologist using new technology to forage for
information in the head of the comatose murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Debuting in second place was Spike Lee's ''The Original Kings of
Comedy,'' documenting a tour by Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley and
other comics. The movie grossed $11.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the top 12 films took in $86.7 million, off 3.2 percent
over the same weekend last year and continuing a downward trend
from Hollywood's record summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The top 20 movies at North American theaters Friday through
Sunday, followed by distribution studio, gross, number of theater
locations, average receipts per location, total gross and number of
weeks in release, as compiled Monday by Exhibitor Relations Co.
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   1. ''The Cell,'' New Line, $17.5 million, 2,411 locations,
$7,265 average, $17.5 million, one week.
</P>
<P>
   2. ''The Original Kings of Comedy,'' Paramount, $11.1 million,
