<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Couch, Browns Offense Struggling  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- The Cleveland Browns haven't run the ball or
passed it very well. However, they're doing a nice job of
protecting quarterback Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   On and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Couch, Cleveland's second-year QB, hasn't been sacked in three
exhibition starts behind the first-team offensive line. However, he
has taken some hard hits in newspapers, on television and radio
talk shows for his sub-par play.
</P>
<P>
   ''You feel bad for the guy,'' said Ty Detmer. ''I've been there
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Detmer was at Browns' practice for the first time Monday since
undergoing season-ending surgery after tearing his right Achilles'
tendon two weeks ago while scrambling at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody needed a pep talk it was Detmer, whose leg is in a
cast from the knee down for the next six weeks. He drove around the
practice fields on an electrical scooter before hopping over to a
bench to meet reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer talked about the disappointment of being out for the
season, and how strange it was watching his teammates on TV. But
mostly Detmer, a nine-year veteran and team leader, said he's been
hurting for Couch, whose struggles have led some Browns fans to
call him ''Tim Slouch.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure once the regular season starts he'll pick it up and
you'll see him playing with a lot more fire and cutting it loose,''
Detmer said. ''In the preseason he's just been afraid to make
mistakes. You feel for the guy because we've all been there at one
time or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch hasn't looked good, and neither has the Browns' offense,
which managed just 156 yards on 50 plays in a 24-0 loss to
Washington on Saturday night. When the starters were on the field,
the offense had no play longer than 10 yards.
</P>
<P>
   There are other, uglier numbers for Cleveland's offense:
</P>
<P>
   -- Zero points in the past eight quarters.
</P>
<P>
   -- Six points in the last six periods.
</P>
<P>
   -- 18 yards rushing in 13 attempts behind the first-team line.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disappointed in the offense,'' Browns coach Chris Palmer
said. ''The execution has to improve. Our timing on offense isn't
good. We need to practice that and continue to grow. We've got to
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some excuses for the offensive doldrums, though.
</P>
<P>
   Couch has been without wide receiver Kevin Johnson -- his main
target last season -- the past two games. Johnson has missed almost
three weeks of practice with a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   And Errict Rhett, expected to be Cleveland's starting running
back this season, missed the Washington game with a broken nose.
</P>
<P>
   The last two weeks, Couch has been throwing to three new
receivers. JaJuan Dawson and Dennis Northcutt are rookies and David
Patten is in his first year in Cleveland after signing as a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Couch is still getting comfortable running new
offensive coordinator Pete Carmichael's system. One of the new
wrinkles is Couch using more three-step drops to get rid of the
ball quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dismal stats from Saturday, Couch saw some
positives.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were some opportunities there that we could have taken
advantage of,'' Couch said. ''A guy messing up here, a guy messing
up there. We just have to work to clean that mess up. The positive
sign is there were opportunities to make plays. We've just got to
go out and make them.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch admits the onslaught of criticism has effected his play
and said he has sought out others to help tune it out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've talked to my brother quite a bit and some guys on the
team that I'm good friends with,'' he said. ''You just have to get
some stuff off your chest now and then and have somebody to talk
to. I've definitely got those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them is cornerback Corey Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the criticism of Tim has been very harsh,'' Fuller
said. ''It takes time. There's not a potion that can make you go
out there and have Joe Montana's success. ... I told him, 'Look,
fans are like the weather. If you win, they're with you. Lose,
they're like a hurricane. Don't let them get to your psyche.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
