<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Officials Reach To Rebels  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- Zapatista rebels in Chiapas
state once took up arms against Mexico's ruling party. Although
recent elections have eroded the party's power, it won't be easy to
convince rebels to give up their guns, the state's governor-elect
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Salazar, who defeated a PRI candidate in Sunday's voting,
says the rebels will likely wait to see action from the new state
and national governments. The victory came several weeks after the
PRI lost its hold on the nation's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way to gain credibility with the Zapatistas ... is with
acts,'' not words, Salazar said in a radio interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A four-year lull since peace talks stalled in 1996 has
complicated efforts to end the long-simmering rebellion, which
flared in 1994 as rebels took up arms to demand greater rights for
Mexico's Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ''The conflict is going through a situation much graver than in
'94 ... because one must rebuild all the bases and conditions of
the peace process,'' Miguel Alvarez of the Chiapas-based Advisory
Services for Peace told a news conference on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With 95 percent of the vote counted from Sunday's election,
coalition candidate Salazar had 52 percent, a lead of 6 percentage
points over Sami David of the ruling PRI, or Institutional
Revolutionary Party. That ended the PRI's seven-decade rule in the
region. Salazar duplicated Vicente Fox's feat in the July 2
presidential vote.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Zapatista National Liberation Army in the
Lacondon jungle told The Associated Press over the weekend that
they remain skeptical of any government and were waiting to see
proof of goodwill, not mere promises.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels encouraged people to vote on Sunday, but insisted
they were neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Though open warfare lasted only two weeks in 1994, armed
pro-government villagers have repeatedly clashed with Zapatista
supporters in the mountains and canyons of rural Chiapas since
then, aggravating mistrust between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Local land disputes have turned bloody, as in the village of
Acteal, when pro-government gunmen massacred 45 Zapatista
sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks stalled in 1996 after the only significant accord,
on expanding the rights of Indian communities. A commission of
federal lawmakers -- which included Salazar -- drew up a proposed law
to enact it. The Zapatistas endorsed it. The federal government
balked, claiming it would compromise national sovereignty
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Fox repeated his vow to present that proposed law
to Congress ''at the start of my term'' and said he would meet
another Zapatista demand, to pull back troops, ''as soon as the
state of law is re-established.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Fox and Salazar say they are ready to meet the rebels
face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar's experience in negotiations with the Zapatistas has
raised hope that he will know how to deal with them. He has
promised to crack down on paramilitary groups and remove government
support for them.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar also promised to consult the Zapatistas on political
reforms rather than imposing them -- something that would respect
the sense of pride and power the impoverished Indian guerrillas won
in taking up arms.
</P>
<P>
   The government will have to find a peaceful way to let them keep
that pride while also settling the grievances of other communities
who have conflicts with the Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   Another rebel movement based in nearby states, the Revolutionary
Army of the Insurgent People, has already vowed that despite Fox's
victory, it will continue its armed struggle against free-market
economic policies it says hurt the poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 2002 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000821.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glover of Clemson In Baltusrol Lead  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, N.J. (AP) -- Jeff Wilson, who stood side by side
with Tiger Woods during the U.S. Open awards ceremony as the low
amateur, shot a 4-under-par 67 to share the first-round lead in the
100th U.S. Amateur on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Glover of Clemson and David Miller of Georgia also had 67s
on a mild, sunny day in which the Upper and Lower courses at the
famed Baltusrol Golf Club yielded only 20 sub-par rounds to the
field of 312 players.
</P>
<P>
   James Driscoll of Virginia, a quarterfinalist last year, was
alone at 68, a shot ahead of a group of eight that included Georgia
Tech teammates Bryce Molder and Carlton Forrester, and Luke Donald
of England, the 1999 NCAA champion for Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Byrd, a member of the 1999 U.S. Walker Cup team and a
teammate of Glover, headed another large group at 70. John Harris,
the 1993 U.S. Amateur champion; Danny Green, the current U.S.
Mid-Amateur champ; and Andy Miller, the son of former PGA Tour star
Johnny Miller, also were in that group.
</P>
<P>
   Glover of Greenville, S.C.; David Miller of Daphne, Ala.; and
Wilson, a reinstated amateur from Suisun, Calif., who pretty much
gave up golf in 1994, all played on the somewhat easier Upper
Course. The par-71, 6,887-yard layout will be used when match play
starts Wednesday for the 64 survivors of stroke play.
</P>
<P>
   Molder, Forrester and Kevin Warrick, a sophomore at the
University of West Florida, were the only players to break par (70)
on the 7,116-yard Lower Course, which has been the site of four
U.S. Opens since 1954, including the Jack Nicklaus-Isao Aoki
showdown in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of notable players are going to have to hustle to make
the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kuchar, the 1997 Amateur champion, shot a 77 on the Upper
Course.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Curtis, the winner of the recent Players' Amateur and a
semifinalist in this event a year ago, shot a 73 on the Lower
Course.
</P>
<P>
   On a day in which college golfers dominated the leaderboard,
Wilson carried the banner for the 30-something crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old who played without any success the PGA Tour in
1990 had six birdies and two bogeys in one of the final pairings of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I can play as well as anybody out here, I guess,''
said Wilson, a car salesman who had got his amateur status restored
in 1997 so he could play in some best-ball tournaments. ''I don't
compete that much, so that would be the one thing that would be my
drawback. But I have played a lot of competitive golf.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament that Wilson likes to recall is the U.S. Open, the
one that Woods won by 15 strokes at Pebble Beach. Wilson finished
35 shots behind him, but that was enough to earn him the gold medal
and a chance to stand by Woods at the awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just blown away,'' Wilson said. ''Here was a guy who had
just made one of the best performances in any sport and he
congratulated me on being the low amateur. I was sitting there,
''What are you talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the greatest performances of all time and he took time
out to congratulate me for shooting 20-over par,'' Wilson said. ''I
think that guy is something special. That was something to
behold.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has competed in three other amateurs, 1982, '85 and '99.
</P>
<P>
   Glover, who failed to qualify for match play in his two other
appearances in the Amateur, had six birdies and two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   David Miller, who also played late Monday, had five birdies and
one bogey in a round in which he had 10 one-putt greens.
</P>
<P>
   David Gossett turned professional recently, so he is not
defending his title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
