<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State says city's infighting symptom of government breakdown  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Public infighting between Camden's City
Council, the mayor and his administration illustrates the collapse
of local government there and ''underscores the need'' for a state
takeover, Department of Community Affairs Commissioner Jane M.
Kenny said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see that there are just some fundamental things that just
don't work in the governance there,'' Kenny said. ''There are some
underlying problems. The center doesn't hold in Camden.''
</P>
<P>
   Days after the council asked indicted Mayor Milton Milan to
resign, Kenny said she will continue lobbying legislators to
approve a takeover of the state's poorest city. Part of her pitch
is to show them just how bad Camden's administration is, Kenny
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the City Council unanimously approved a resolution
asking Milan to resign. Earlier in the week, city attorney John A.
Misci Jr., 36, resigned claiming the council had created an
''unhealthy, openly hostile, racist and retaliatory workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Milan also recently directed city department heads not to talk
to council members. Instead, council members must go through
business administrator Preston Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   But Camden's problems go beyond these public battles, Kenny
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It certainly is chaotic and it's clearly something that
underscores the need for stability,'' Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
   State management teams now have the power to supervise city
spending and hiring. But the state needs more power to correct the
underlying problems, Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny and her staff have been meeting with legislators since the
Whitman administration proposed the takeover legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators worried publicly about the takeover's impact on
the traditionally strong policy of letting individual
municipalities govern themselves without direct state intervention.
Others claimed a takeover subverts the democratic process by
removing elected leaders from power.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposal is passed, Camden would become the first city to
have its operations fully assumed by state government.
</P>
<P>
   A version of the bill was introduced in the Senate before the
summer recess and no committee hearing is scheduled. No action has
been taken in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   In her sessions with lawmakers, Kenny said she addressed those
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is a very superficial concern, an immediate
concern,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny said a prime concern should be providing public services
to Camden residents. Lawmakers should also be looking to hold city
administrators accountable for the state aid, she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 cents of every dollar Camden spends comes from state
relief funds, Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
   The first public step in the state's control of Camden came the
day after Milan was charged in an indictment with extortion, money
laundering and mail fraud. Federal authorities said Milan accepted
payoffs and gifts from city contractors and took bribes from
organized crime figures.
</P>
<P>
   The state gave Milan two weeks to correct long-standing
problems. The state finance board said he didn't and on April 14
voted to place the city under supervision. That prompted the state
attorney general's office to file a lawsuit that asked a judge to
approve the control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Milan threatened to place the city in bankruptcy last year
before he accepted a deal to allow a state financial review board
some oversight of operations. But despite that monitoring, the
state alleges, Camden officials continued to ignore the problems.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the state said Camden filed annual audits more
than two years after they were due. When the audits were filed,
some contained a notice from the auditor that the examinations
could not be done because Camden kept no records of its
expenditures. Camden also overspent its budget by nearly $500,000
in 1998, according to the state's legal brief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-21-00 2034 </TRAILER>
