<HEADLINE> Angels Protest Game Over Umps Call  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- The Anaheim Angels filed a protest over an
umpire's call in the fourth inning of Monday night's game against
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The bases were loaded when Ben Molina hit a popup to short
center field.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett slid for the ball trying to catch it, but it landed
safely. Second baseman Jose Offerman picked up the ball and threw
it to third; although the ball beat Tim Salmon to the bag, third
baseman Lou Merloni was not standing on the base, so Salmon should
have been safe.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that third base umpire Jerry Meals had gone into
the outfield to make a call on Everett's play. After a short delay,
second base umpire Derryl Cousins called Salmon out.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia came out to argue, then returned to
the dugout. He came out again to say that he was protesting the
call.
</P>
</TEXT>
