<HEADLINE> Central Park re-sprayed for West Nile Virus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP)- Central Park was scheduled to be re-sprayed with
pesticide early Tuesday morning as part of the city's continuing
battle against the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   The pesticide Anvil, which was sprayed at the 843-acre park over
the weekend, is most effective when applied twice, Health
Department officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In Queens, pesticide-spraying trucks were scheduled to drive
through a two-mile area of Woodside and the Rockaways from 10 p.m.
Monday until 5 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester, spraying was scheduled for Rye Brook, Port
Chester, Mount Vernon, Pelham Manor, Pelham Village and Irvington.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, spraying of the pesticide was set for Monday
night in West Islip, West Bay Shore, Brightwaters, Patchogue
Village, East Patchogue, Bellport Village, North Bellport and
Brookhaven Hamlet.
</P>
