<HEADLINE> Sunken Norwegian Ferry Wreck Raised  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- A Norwegian salvage team on Monday raised
the battered wreck of a high-speed passenger ferry that ran aground
in November and sank, killing 16 people.
</P>
<P>
   The 138-foot twin-hulled vessel went down with 85 people aboard
during a nighttime run between the cities of Stavanger and Bergen
on Norway's west coast, near Boemla Island 250 miles west of the
capital Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Ministry of Justice ordered the wreck raised to
find out why the new vessel, which had the latest in navigation and
rescue aids, ran aground and why some of its life rafts failed to
deploy.
</P>
<P>
   Salvage crews worked through the weekend to place a frame under
the wreck, which lay under about 330 feet of water. Crews moved the
wreck into shallower waters on Sunday and lifted it onto a barge
Monday for transport to a nearby shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian-built ferry was among the most modern serving
Norway's long coast. An investigating commission has postponed its
conclusions until its experts can examine the wreckage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 2046 </TRAILER>
