<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, Aug. 21, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Declared Cancer-Free
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Senator John McCain's office announced today that tests on
lymph nodes and tissue removed during the skin cancer surgery confirmed that his
skin cancer didn't spread. The former GOP presidential candidate underwent more
than five hours of surgery on Saturday to remove melanoma, the most dangerous
form of skin cancer, from his temple and upper arm. Pathologists completed the
final review of the tissues around the cancers and found no sign the melanoma
had spread, said Todd Harris, a McCain spokesman.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Quest for Sub Survivors Ends
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The effort to reach the crew aboard a sunken Russian submarine
ended as divers announced Monday that none of the 118 sailors aboard could have
survived. Norwegian divers who finally opened the escape hatch and forced their
way into the hull of the Kursk after working in the Arctic depths for more than
24 hours said the submarine was completely flooded. There was no sign that any
of the crew had survived for long inside the mangled warship 350 feet below the
surface.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pipe Blast Could Spur Safety Bills
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A New Mexico pipeline explosion that killed 11 campers may
spur Congress to act on long-stalled legislation to intensify inspections of
underground pipelines. ''It's galling to think that more tragedies could happen
while these bills sit in committee,'' said Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., a sponsor
of one of the bills. A man died today in a Lubbock, Texas, hospital, the 11th
victim of a Saturday explosion in a buried natural gas pipeline near Carlsbad,
N.M. Five children were among those killed after the pre-dawn explosion swept
flames down the Pecos River's banks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
US Envoy: Mideast Progress Blocked
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank (AP) -- President Clinton's top Mideast envoy, on a
mission to prod forward the Israelis and Palestinians after the failure of last
month's Camp David summit, said differences are still blocking a deal after
meeting Monday with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. Last month's
U.S.-sponsored summit made some progress, Dennis Ross said, but ''there is also
no question about the differences that remain, and those differences have to be
overcome if we want to reach and agreement.'' Ross, who met Friday with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, said he would hold another round of talks with the
two leaders and their negotiating teams.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ford Halts Production at 3 Truck Plants
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- For more than a week, Ford Motor Co. will halt production at
three truck plants to free up 70,000 tires for use as replacements in a recall
of 6.5 million Firestone tires. The plants in St. Paul, Minn.; Edison, N.J.; and
Hazelwood, Mo., will close from Aug. 28 to Sept. 8 so that 15-inch tires used in
production of Ford Explorer/Mercury Mountaineer sport utility vehicles and Ford
Ranger pickups can be sent to Ford and Lincoln/Mercury dealers. The plants
employ about 6,000 workers, who will still get paid.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Debby Threatens Caribbean Islands
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILIPSBURG, St. Maarten (AP) -- Speeding west at near hurricane strength,
Tropical Storm Debby threatened several northeast Caribbean islands still
recovering from last year's storm damage. Schools closed, people rushed to buy
emergency supplies and governments prepared shelters. Tourists crowded airports
to flee the storm and cruise ships turned away from the winds and rain. The
fourth named storm of the Atlantic season emerged with unnerving suddenness as
the season's first threat to land.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Most Verizon Workers Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The majority of striking Verizon Communications employees
returned to work today and began sorting through a backlog of 280,000 repair
requests and new installation orders. The company, meanwhile, continued talks
with one bargaining unit as picket lines remained up in six states and the
District of Columbia. Members of the Communications Workers of America remained
on the picket lines today in Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland,
Virginia, West Virginia and the District of Columbia.
</P>
