<HEADLINE> Callers Vie in Canada 'Millionaire'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A Canadian version of the U.S. television quiz
show ''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?'' attracted more than 750,000
phone calls from people wanting to be contestants.
</P>
<P>
   The program will be taped Sept. 7 in New York, with 10 finalists
competing for the top prize.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Vale, vice president of programming and communications
at CTV, a Canadian television network, said Monday the special
phone line set up for possible contestants received 759,937 calls
from Aug. 9 until midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Each caller paid $1.35 for the chance to correctly answer five
questions, and Vale said 3,741 callers succeeded. Further screening
by computer and telephone calls will determine the finalists, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Vale, the U.S. version of the show hosted by Regis
Philbin attracts an average of more than 2 million Canadian
viewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
