<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: People See Gore in New Light  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore is getting a second look from the
American voters, post-convention polls indicate, and they generally
like what they see -- from his leadership skills to his handling of
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS News, ABC-Washington Post and CNN-USA Today-Gallup polls
indicate Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Gore are now in a
dead heat -- about a 15-point swing for Gore in all three polls
since before last week's Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of people who view Gore favorably has improved
significantly, both in the CBS poll and the Gallup poll, to levels
that are now comparable to Bush's ratings. In the CBS poll, 45
percent viewed Gore favorably and 27 percent unfavorably -- the same
as the results for Bush. Six in 10 viewed Gore and Bush favorably
in the Gallup poll.
</P>
<P>
   Six in 10 said in the Gallup poll that Gore has the personality
and leadership qualities a president should have, about the same as
for Bush. Fewer than half in July said Gore has such qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was rated stronger than Bush on health care, Social
Security, education, abortion rights, prescription drugs, and
campaign finance reform in the Gallup poll. Bush led on national
defense and they were about even on foreign affairs, guns and
handling the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   All three polls gave Gore improved marks on the quality of
leadership, which had been a solid Bush advantage for months. Gore
was seen as having strong leadership qualities by just more than
six in 10, up from 55 percent in the Gallup poll in July. Bush was
seen as a strong leader by almost seven in 10, about the same as in
July before the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was seen as having an appealing personality by 65 percent
in the ABC-Washington Post poll, while 51 percent said that of
Gore. But three-fourths said Gore has the right kind of experience
to be president, compared with six of 10 who said that of Bush.
Gore was seen as more likely to understand the problems of ordinary
people.
</P>
<P>
   Six in 10 in the CBS poll said Gore can be trusted to keep his
word, up from 47 percent in July and about the same as Bush's
rating on that measure now. Six in 10 said Gore has made it clear
what he would do as president, while half said that of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Three quarters in that poll said Gore would ensure that the
economy remains strong, while six in 10 said that of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The boost in poll numbers following a convention can evaporate
as quickly as it appears and some political pollsters said this
particular round of weekend surveys can be Democrat-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS poll of 956 registered voters was taken Friday through
Sunday and has an error margin of 3 percentage points. The CNN-USA
Today-Gallup poll of 697 likely voters was taken Friday and
Saturday and has an error margin of 4 percentage points. The
ABC-Washington Post poll of 896 registered voters taken Friday
through Sunday has an error margin of 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.cbsnews.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cnn.com
</P>
<P>
   http://abcnews.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 2144 </TRAILER>
