<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spraying for West Nile delayed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Three upstate counties delayed Round Two of
spraying for mosquitoes infected with the West Nile virus Monday,
citing cool temperatures and predictions of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Nighttime temperatures here have dipped below 50 degrees,
lessening mosquito activity and therefore the likelihood of
mosquitoes being killed by the spraying.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials in Albany, Rensselaer and Schenectady counties
had planned a second spraying of the insecticide Anvil for
Wednesday. The first round was completed on Aug. 11 and 12. The
spraying is aimed to cover a two-mile radius of where an infected
baby crow was found on Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the New York State Department of Health reported
that a crow found dead on a city of Albany street tested positive
for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was likely mosquitoes fed on the bird in
Albany, but that it was also possible the bird contracted the
disease elsewhere then flew into Albany.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the virus have been found in either dead birds or
mosquitoes in 21 counties across the state and in three boroughs of
New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
