<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florida 'Stiltsville' Still Stands  </HEADLINE>
By ALEX VEIGA
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The group of aging houses propped on poles inside
Biscayne National Park known as Stiltsville will be allowed to
stand, but homeowners' leases will not be renewed, National Park
Service officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Stiltsville won't be torn down Dec. 1, as feared by homeowners
who've been fighting to preserve the seven structures built over
the water a few miles south of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But under the plan, the Park Service will not rebuild the homes
if they are destroyed or severely damaged during a storm.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make sure that those structures are used for the
public,'' said Linda Canzanelli, Biscayne National Park
superintendent. ''We want to make sure that those are safe ... for
folks to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiltsville dates to the 1920s and 1930s, when fishermen built
shacks in the area. By the 1940s, homes were being built, mostly
used for retreats and parties.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, Stiltsville boasted 25 homes, as high as 50 feet
above Biscayne Bay. Hurricanes and fires have taken their toll.
</P>
<P>
   Duff Matson, who co-owns a Stiltsville home, said the plan would
not ensure homes would be preserved and questioned Biscayne
National Park's ability maintain the structures.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've gotta have blood, sweat and tears to keep maintaining
them, and money,'' Matson said. ''So they're going to
disintegrate''
</P>
<P>
   Government engineers will examine the homes to determine how
structurally sound they are, and any found to be unsound may be
taken down or mothballed, preserved for people to see but not
inhabit, Canzanelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a ruse for the total destruction of the houses,'' Matson
said. ''Some will be called engineering unsound ... So they'll
remove it, and that's how they'll be discarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiltsville homeowners have been trying to reach an agreement
that will preserve the homes.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service owns the area underneath the
structures. The homeowners' lease with the government, signed
almost 30 years ago, had been set to expire Dec. 1, 1999 and
Biscayne National Park had planned to reclaim the houses and
destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   In November, homeowners and National Park Service officials
agreed to give themselves a year to negotiate a resolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 2202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
