<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds 7, Phillies 4  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Dmitri Young hit an upper-deck grand slam and
Barry Larkin got his 2,000th hit in the same inning Monday night as
the Cincinnati Reds beat the Philadelphia Phillies 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Young's first career slam highlighted a six-run third inning off
Randy Wolf (9-7) that sent the Reds to only their second victory in
seven games. Chris Stynes had four hits and scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Perez had three doubles and drove in three runs for the
Phillies, who lost for the seventh time in eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati had two franchise moments as it batted around in the
third for a 7-1 lead. Larkin, the team captain, lined a run-scoring
double to left for his 2,000th hit, then stood at second and waved
as the crowd of 21,558 gave a standing ovation and chanted his
first name.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin became the first major league shortstop to have at least
2,000 hits, 170 homers and 350 stolen bases. He's the fourth player
with 2,000 hits for Cincinnati, joining Pete Rose (3,358), Dave
Concepcion (2,326) and Johnny Bench (2,048).
</P>
<P>
   After Wolf hit Ken Griffey Jr. on the arm with a pitch and
walked Dante Bichette, Young hit the first pitch into the first row
of the upper deck in left -- the 34th red-seat homer in the
stadium's 30-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The only other red-seat slam by a Reds player was the first ever
hit into the upper deck -- by Tony Perez on Aug. 11, 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Young also had a single and a double in a free-swinging
performance, hitting the first pitch in each of his first three
at-bats. He got an intentional walk in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf gave up seven runs and seven hits in three innings,
matching the shortest start of his career. He lasted only three
innings in a 10-2 loss at Houston on May 23.
</P>
<P>
   In his last three starts, Wolf has given up 21 runs in 15 1-3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Harnisch (5-6) struggled despite the big lead, giving up
nine hits and four walks in 5 1-3 innings. Angry after giving up
consecutive walks to load the bases in the sixth, Harnisch walked
to the dugout at a fast clip after he was replaced and slammed his
glove and hat against the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Perez had run-scoring doubles in the second and sixth off
Harnisch and drove in another run by hitting into a forceout in the
fourth. He doubled again in the eighth, but Danny Graves relieved
and got four outs for his 21st save in 24 chances.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Bobby Abreu, who batted leadoff for the first time in his
career Sunday and went 2-for-3, hit leadoff again Monday and went
1-for-3 with a pair of walks. ... Scott Rolen singled in the fifth,
ending an 0-for-17 slump. ... Griffey and Phillies Doug Glanville,
Mike Lieberthal and Pat Burrell were on the field early to film a
segment for a movie tentatively called ''Summer Catch.'' It's about
a pitcher who makes it to the big leagues and gives up a homer to
Griffey in his first appearance. ... Harnisch threw the Reds' 82nd
wild pitch of the season, one shy of the club record. ... Young's
upper-deck homer was the first by a Red this season and the fourth
overall. Mark McGwire, Preston Wilson and Moises Alou also have
reached the red seats. ... Griffey went 2-for-4, extending his
hitting streak to seven games and raising his average to a
season-high .257.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 2230 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000821.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks' Durazo Faces Surgery  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Arizona first baseman Erubiel Durazo could be
facing a second operation on his sore right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Durazo, who went on the disabled list for the third time this
season because of soreness in the wrist on Sunday, had an MRI exam
on Monday. Afterward, Diamondbacks team doctors were
uncharacteristically mum on the results.
</P>
<P>
   ''Erubiel Durazo is having recurrent problems with his right
wrist that was operated on earlier this season,'' Dr. Don Sheridan
said. ''At the present time Erubiel is weighing his options. We
should have more information in the next day or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan said Durazo asked that no further information be
released at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd like to leave it at that at this point so Erubiel can
discuss this with his family,'' Sheridan said. ''He's a team
player. He wants to do what's best for his team and at this time
he's considering all the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The options could include undergoing surgery now, and likely
being lost for the season, or putting off the surgery until after
this season and trying to play through it in Arizona's drive for
the playoffs in September.
</P>
<P>
   Durazo was on the disabled list from May 30 to June 23 while
recovering from surgery to repair torn cartilage in the wrist. Just
four days later, on June 27, he went on the DL again with wrist
pain. He was activated July 12.
</P>
<P>
   Durazo said he aggravated the wrist injury when he fouled off a
pitch in his final at-bat in Saturday night's 11-3 victory over the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Durazo was one of baseball's big surprises as a rookie in 1999,
working his way up to the majors quickly from Double-A El Paso. In
52 games with Arizona last season, Durazo batted .329 with 11 home
runs and 30 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's hitting .265 in 67 games with eight home runs
and 33 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   After a 5-for-20 road trip, Durazo was sent to Tucson for nine
games earlier this month to work on his swing. He was recalled Aug.
11, and was 2-for-4 Saturday night in just his third start since
rejoining the Diamondbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-21-00 2241 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000821.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo 9, Toronto 8  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- Jay Ponciano pitched a two-hitter and
Dustin Corl hit a two-run homer as Vancouver beat Bellaire, Texas,
5-0 in the Little League World Series on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Having already made their statement by beating the California
powerhouses in the Western Regional, Vancouver -- playing its Series
opener -- wasn't about to be rattled playing on a national stage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Playing in the Western Regional championship game, I got used
to (the pressure),'' said Ponciano, who struck out seven, walked
one, and never allowed a runner past second base. ''I just have to
do it. It's my job and I got to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Evans had two hits and scored twice for Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Atherton and Drew Zizinia had the lone hits -- both singles
-- for Bellaire (1-1), coming off a 3-0 victory over Goffstown,
N.H., on Sunday. Bellaire has one pool game remaining, Tuesday
against Davenport, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ''We actually thought we had an advantage going in having played
last night and they haven't played,'' Bellaire manager Terry McConn
said. ''But hats off to them, they're a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Late starts are nothing new for Vancouver, said manager Tom
Peavey.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the Western Regionals, we were the last team to arrive. It
took us 28 hours to get there, so these kids are used to being
late,'' Peavey said.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver struck first with two runs in the third when Evans got
on with a one-out single, and Corl followed with a home run that
just cleared the left-center field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Corl said he was giving his home-run ball to ''T.J.,'' Tyler
Jacobs, a 6-year-old who underwent surgery in mid-June to remove a
benign brain tumor, who has become the team's inspirational leader.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver broke the game open with a three-run fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Julian Vandervelde's two-run homer keyed Davenport to a
5-0 victory over winless Goffstown. Ruben Mavarez pitched a
two-hitter as Maracaibo, Venezuela, evened its record at 1-1 with a
3-0 win over Dhahran, Saudi Arabia. And Tokyo improved to 2-0 -- and
all but mathematically clinched a spot in the pool final -- by
hanging on for a 9-8 victory over Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Vandervelde, 6-foot-2 and 231 pounds, carried a big bat for
Davenport, which marked the U.S. Central region's first Series win
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 1-0, the first baseman slammed a two-run, 239-foot shot
off the hedges beyond the center-field wall in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We grow them big,'' Davenport manager Matt Kolar said. ''I
don't know how many teams have one guy that can put the ball out of
the park every other time up if you're not careful. And that's big
because runs are hard to come by.''
</P>
<P>
   Starter Dan O'Donnell -- 10-0 in All-Star play -- went the
distance, throwing a two-hitter and striking out seven. Michael
Mitchell had a hit and scored three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Including Sunday's 3-0 loss to Bellaire, Goffstown has managed
just three hits in the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Maracaibo may have won, but manager Eduvino Quevedo wasn't
pleased with his team's sputtering offense.
</P>
<P>
   In two games, the Venezuelans have stranded 14 runners.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're expecting a better pace out of themselves on the
offensive side,'' Quevedo said through interpreter Micah Hughes.
''It's his bats, he doesn't know, he's trying to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Figueroa had two hits and drove in a run, while Mavarez had
a hit and RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Hecht doubled and Chris Griffith singled for Dhahran,
playing its Series opener.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Riley Arp allowed eight hits, but was undone by two
errors that led to Maracaibo's three-run second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dhahran manager Al Griffith blamed ''butterflies'' on his team's
early miscues.
</P>
<P>
   The day's first game was the most exciting as Toronto's six-run,
sixth-inning rally -- capped by Julian Olibera's two-out, three-run
homer -- fell one run short against Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Daiki Ichimura, the second reliever of the inning, got Ozzie
Diaz to pop out to second baseman Yuusaku Nakanishi to end the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, Toronto manager David Trimble was bolstered by
the way his team didn't give up.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me put it this way. We'd love to have a shot at Japan
again in the playoff game,'' Trimble said, referring to Thursday's
International Pool final.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo starter Kazuma Yamada threw a three-hitter, smacked two
home runs and drove in six runs, giving him a Series-high eight
RBIs in two games.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.littleleague.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
