<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bucs Release Brad Culpepper  </HEADLINE>
By FRED GOODALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Defensive tackle Brad Culpepper was among 12
players released Monday night by the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, clearing
the way for second-year pro Anthony McFarland to move into the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper, entering his sixth season with the Bucs, started 61
games over the past four years and in 1998 he led one of the
league's top defenses in sacks with nine. He's fourth on the club's
career sack list with 33.
</P>
<P>
   The decision caught the ninth-year pro by surprise. He received
a call from the team as he and his wife were headed to dinner about
9 p.m., and drove to the team's training complex instead.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland, a No. 1 pick who played sparingly as a rookie in
1999, will take over Culpepper's spot.
</P>
<P>
   ''They feel he's ready to play and they don't really see me in a
backup role,'' Culpepper said, adding that ''time will tell'' if
the Bucs made the correct decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe I'm a starter in this league, and I feel I have the
film to prove it,'' he said. ''By no means is my football career
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven other players were also waived as the roster was trimmed
to 72, including seven NFL Europe exemptions who don't count toward
the league-mandated limit of 65. The biggest name was third-string
quarterback Scott Milanovich.
</P>
<P>
   Also released were center Eric DeGroh, receivers Tavarus Hogans
and Michael Williams, defensive linemen Aaron Humphrey and Damonte
McKenzie, linebackers Antony Jordan and Kinnon Tatum, cornerback
Terrance Parrish, fullback John Waerig and punter John Shay.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tony Dungy was not available for comment after Culpepper's
release. However, the team issued a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brad has been a real good player for us for a number of years,
and this was a very difficult decision,'' Dungy said. ''We wanted
to do this now to give Brad every opportunity to hook on with
another football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Dungy talked about how painful the cut process
can be.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the same, year in and year out. You get close to guys.
Guys come in, especially the way we do it now, you get guys who
sign with you in February and March and they've been here all
summer and spring, worked hard and done everything you've asked,''
Dungy said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no easy way to tell someone you're fired. In normal
(employment) situations, you don't say I'm going to fire 20 guys
this week and fire 15 guys next week and know that it's coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Milanovich, who spent parts of four seasons with the Bucs, was
re-signed late last season after Trent Dilfer was injured. He was
3-of-8 for 9 yards and was intercepted once this preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't totally unexpected,'' said Milanovich, who has
thrown three regular season passes during his career. ''I've been
around long enough to know how things work. So I was prepared for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Milanovich's release improved the chances that rookie Joe
Hamilton, a seventh-round draft pick from Georgia Tech, will make
the team as the third quarterback behind Shaun King and Eric Zeier.
Although Milanovich plans to move to New York and complete work on
his college degree, there's still a chance he could wind up with
the Bucs if one of the club's quarterbacks is injured.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were some things to that effect said,'' Milanovich said.
''But you just have to kind of wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The cuts didn't include any safeties, a position depleted by
injuries during training camp. With Shevin Smith dislocating his
left big toe during Sunday's 31-21 victory over New England, the
team is down to just four healthy safeties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shevin is going to be out quite a while. He's got a turf toe
with some ligament damage in there, and it's going to be an
indefinite period of time for him,'' Dungy said, adding that it's
too soon to tell if the third-year pro could wind up on injured
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll have to wait and see,'' he added. ''But, its not going
to be a one- or two-week deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
