<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial gets underway for officer wounded in Jamestown  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MAYVILLE, N.Y. (AP) - Testimony began Monday in September's
shooting of a Jamestown police officer, allegedly by a teen-ager
police had hoped would lead them to an area drug kingpin.
</P>
<P>
   During more than 90 minutes of testimony, Jamestown police
Detective David P. Mitchell said he was shot by James E. Lewis Jr.
on Sept. 15, the night he and his partner were to meet Lewis for
information on a drug supplier from Rochester named Tracy Roach.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, then 18, had been released from police custody earlier in
the day after being taken in on drug sale charges. Mitchell told
the court Lewis had agreed to work as a confidential informant.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Lewis) was very,very important to me,'' Mitchell said, ''If I
was responsible for knocking Tracy Roach off the drug trade in
Jamestown, then I was making a big dent in the supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Roach has since been charged with drug sales in Rochester and is
now in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell and partner Scott DePietro, who was to testify Tuesday,
were apparently driving an unmarked car in the neighborhood where
they were to meet Lewis. Lewis allegedly opened fire with a handgun
at close range as Mitchell rolled down his window.
</P>
<P>
   Police found Lewis at the nearby home of an acquaintance and
quickly surrounded it with a SWAT team. Lewis surrendered after a
standoff that lasted more than five hours.
</P>
<P>
   Jamestown is a city of about 35,000 located 60 miles south of
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, a 17-year veteran of the police department, was the
first officer shot in the line of duty there in 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
